"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438816","Department for International Development","false","2015-12-16","<p>The UK has pledged over £1.1 billion in response to the Syria crisis, of which £559 million has been allocated to support refugees in the region and vulnerable host communities. The vast majority of refugees in the region live in host communities rather than camps.</p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2015-12-16T13:40:23.437Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438816/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438816/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438816/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-12-10","Syria: Refugees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what funding and other resources her Department has provided for Syrian refugee camps.","false","Biography information for Scott Mann","North Cornwall","Scott Mann","902756"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438817","Department for International Development","false","2015-12-16","<p>In the financial year 2014/15, the UK spent just under £150 million in humanitarian assistance inside Syria and around £125 million in the surrounding region. This has provided lifesaving support and helped ensure Syrian children can remain in education.</p>","Putney","Justine Greening",,"2015-12-16T13:28:02.583Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438817/answer","Biography information for Justine Greening","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438817/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438817/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-12-10","Syria: Refugees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, how much her Department has spent on humanitarian assistance in (a) Syria and (b) neighbouring countries receiving Syrian refugees in the last two years.","false","Biography information for Lord Davies of Gower","Gower","Byron Davies","902755"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438818","Department for International Development","false","2015-12-16","<p>My department has contributed nearly £16 million for the refugee crisis in Europe this year to date. In the long term we are focussed on using the UK’s aid budget to support refugees to have a viable option to stay where they are by tackling the root causes of migration.</p>","Putney","Justine Greening",,"2015-12-16T17:05:05.707Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438818/answer","Biography information for Justine Greening","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438818/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438818/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-12-10","Refugees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what proportion of Overseas Development Aid her Department used to tackle the refugee crisis in the last 12 months; and how much her Department plans to allocate in future years to tackling that situation.","false","Biography information for Ian Lavery","Wansbeck","Ian Lavery","902758"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438819","Department for International Development","false","2015-12-16","<p>DFID has agreed to fund the ODA-eligible costs of the Syria refugee resettlement scheme for this financial year - discussions are ongoing to determine the precise amount necessary. From next year ODA funding for the scheme will be transferred directly from Treasury to the Home Office.</p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2015-12-16T13:48:31.223Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438819/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438819/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438819/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-12-10","Syria: Refugees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what funding her Department has allocated to support resettlement of Syrian refugees.","false","Biography information for Will Quince","Colchester","Will Quince","902761"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438820","Department for International Development","false","2015-12-16","<p>The UK is currently reviewing all core contributions through the Multilateral Aid Review. We are committed to remaining a world leader in tackling global diseases like HIV/AIDS, tuberculosis and malaria. We will continue to invest in the Global Fund, which has saved 17 million lives.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2015-12-16T13:47:05.527Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438820/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438820/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438820/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-12-10","Global Fund to Fight AIDS, Tuberculosis and Malaria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, if she will make it her policy to continue to invest in the Global Fund to Fight AIDS, Tuberculosis and Malaria.","false","Biography information for Karin Smyth","Bristol South","Karin Smyth","902760"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438821","Department for International Development","false","2015-12-16","<p>The Prime Minister has announced that the government will provide £5.8 billion from the official development assistance budget over the next five years. This will support the Paris Climate Summit outcome and help the most vulnerable countries protect themselves from the effects of climate change and drive clean economic growth.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2015-12-16T13:45:24.307Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438821/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438821/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438821/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-12-10","Developing Countries: Climate Change","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what proportion of the international aid budget she plans to allocate to support communities managing the consequences of climate change in each of the next five years.","false","Biography information for Callum McCaig","Aberdeen South","Callum McCaig","902759"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438822","Department for International Development","false","2015-12-16","<p>The UN assesses that the situation in the Occupied Palestinian Territories (OPTs) is a protracted protection crisis with humanitarian consequences. According to the UN, Palestinians in the OPTs face a range of serious threats including threats to life, liberty and security, destruction of homes and other property, forced displacement, and restrictions on freedom of movement and access to livelihoods.</p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2015-12-16T13:41:30.277Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438822/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438822/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438822/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-12-10","Occupied Territories","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what recent assessment she has made of the humanitarian situation in the Occupied Palestinian Territories.","false","Biography information for Tommy Sheppard","Edinburgh East","Tommy Sheppard","902757"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436553","HM Treasury","false","2015-12-23","<p>The government does not have an explicit target for household or corporate borrowing. The government is adamant not to repeat the mistakes of the past, which is why it created the independent Financial Policy Committee (FPC) within the Bank of England to ensure that emerging risks and vulnerabilities across the financial system as a whole are identified, monitored and effectively addressed.</p>",,"Lord O'Neill of Gatley",,"2015-12-23T10:24:01.173Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436553/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Neill of Gatley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436553/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436553/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-12-09","Debts","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Deighton on 10 February (HL4482), what assessment they have made of what is an acceptable and safe level of borrowing for (1) individuals and households, (2) non-financial corporations, and (3) financial institutions.","false","Biography information for Lord Birt",,"Lord Birt","HL4387"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436554","HM Treasury","false","2015-12-23","<p>As mentioned in the answer of 9 March, the Government does not set a specific target for private sector debt. However, the Financial Policy Committee (FPC), established as a policy committee of the Bank of England, is empowered to identify, assess, monitor and take action in relation to risks across the UK financial system. This includes risks which arise from beyond the core banking sector (such as private sector debt). The FPC actively monitors developments in the aggregate level of credit extended to UK households and private non-financial corporations, and has the macroprudential policy tools required to address any risk it identifies.</p><br /><p>For example, the countercyclical buffer is a macroprudential instrument which is designed to protect the banking sector from periods of excess aggregate credit growth that can contribute to system-wide risk. The countercyclical buffer rate in the UK is currently set at 0%, and is reviewed on a quarterly basis.</p>",,"Lord O'Neill of Gatley","HL4389","2015-12-23T10:23:08.647Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436554/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Neill of Gatley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436554/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436554/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-12-09","Debts","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Deighton on 9 March (HL5261), whether they have identified a threshold level of private-sector or financial corporation debt that might "threaten financial stability", and if so, what that level is, and what steps they plan to take if it is reached.","false","Biography information for Lord Birt",,"Lord Birt","HL4388"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436555","HM Treasury","false","2015-12-23","<p>As mentioned in the answer of 9 March, the Government does not set a specific target for private sector debt. However, the Financial Policy Committee (FPC), established as a policy committee of the Bank of England, is empowered to identify, assess, monitor and take action in relation to risks across the UK financial system. This includes risks which arise from beyond the core banking sector (such as private sector debt). The FPC actively monitors developments in the aggregate level of credit extended to UK households and private non-financial corporations, and has the macroprudential policy tools required to address any risk it identifies.</p><br /><p>For example, the countercyclical buffer is a macroprudential instrument which is designed to protect the banking sector from periods of excess aggregate credit growth that can contribute to system-wide risk. The countercyclical buffer rate in the UK is currently set at 0%, and is reviewed on a quarterly basis.</p>",,"Lord O'Neill of Gatley","HL4388","2015-12-23T10:23:08.71Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436555/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Neill of Gatley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436555/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436555/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-12-09","Debts","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Deighton on 9 March (HL5261), whether they have considered setting an explicit target for private-sector and financial corporation debt, and if not, why not.","false","Biography information for Lord Birt",,"Lord Birt","HL4389"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436556","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-01-14","<p>The data requested is set out in the table below. Data from October and November 2015 will be available after figures for this period have been published in the knife possession sentencing quarterly statistics on <a href="http://www.gov.uk" target="_blank">www.gov.uk</a>. The figures in the tables will be subject to change as the cases that are currently in the system eventually reach a court outcome.</p><br /><p>In July 2015, a new minimum custodial sentence for repeat knife possession came into force. Out of the 456 days covered by this data, there were just 76 days in which the minimum sentence was applicable. The average time from charge to court outcome is 86 days, so it is unlikely that any repeat possession offences could be tried under the new legislation.</p><br /><p>Table 1 shows the number of juvenile cautioning and sentencing occasions for knife possession offences by age group for each month between July 2014 and September 2015.</p><br /><p>Table 2 shows the number of juvenile cautioning and sentencing occasions for knife possession offences, where the juvenile has one previous caution or conviction for the possession of a knife or offensive weapon, by age group for each month between July 2014 and September 2015.</p><br /><p>Table 3 shows the number of juvenile sentencing occasions for knife possession offences resulting in an immediate custodial sentence by age group for each month between July 2014 and September 2015.</p><br /><p>Table 4 shows the number of juvenile cautioning and sentencing occasions for knife possession offences by ethnic appearance for each month between July 2014 and September 2015.</p><br /><p>Table 5 shows the number of juvenile cautioning and sentencing occasions for knife possession offences, where the juvenile has one previous caution or conviction for the possession of a knife or offensive weapon, by ethnic appearance for each month between July 2014 and September 2015.</p><br /><p>Table 6 shows the number of juvenile sentencing occasions for knife possession offences resulting in an immediate custodial sentence by ethnic appearance for each month between July 2014 and September 2015.</p>",,"Lord Faulks",,"2016-01-14T14:15:12.113Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436556/answer","Biography information for Lord Faulks","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436556/answer","Juvenile Knife Possession Jul 14 to Sep 15.xls","Juvenile Knife Possession Jul 2014 to Sep 2015","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436556/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-12-09","Knives: Crime","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many children were (1) convicted of knife possession, (2) convicted of a second offence of knife possession, and (3) sentenced to custody for knife possession offences, in each month between July 2014 and November 2015 inclusive, broken down by ethnicity and by age group.","false","Biography information for Lord Falconer of Thoroton",,"Lord Falconer of Thoroton","HL4390"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436557","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-12-22","<p>The deployment of staff between prisons on detached duty is a regular and normal part of prison resourcing. It allows staff to be allocated from prisons with the capacity to provide them, to those where additional staffing is required.</p><p /> <p>The total amount spent on staff on detached duties above basic salaries could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p><br />",,"Lord Faulks",,"2015-12-22T16:38:13.763Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436557/answer","Biography information for Lord Faulks","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436557/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436557/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-12-09","Young Offender Institutions","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what was the total spent, above basic salaries, on staff on detached duty at young offender institutions in England and Wales in each month between October 2014 and October 2015 inclusive.","false","Biography information for Lord Falconer of Thoroton",,"Lord Falconer of Thoroton","HL4391"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436558","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-12-22","<p>This information is not held centrally. The Ministry of Justice facilitates a wide and varied range of opportunities for volunteers to work with offenders, within prisons and in the community, and also directly recruits volunteers to sit on its Independent Monitoring Boards.</p>",,"Lord Faulks",,"2015-12-22T16:29:11.443Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436558/answer","Biography information for Lord Faulks","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436558/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436558/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-12-09","Prisons: Voluntary Work","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many volunteers there are currently carrying out work in each prison in England and Wales.","false","Biography information for Lord Falconer of Thoroton",,"Lord Falconer of Thoroton","HL4392"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436559","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-12-22","<p>In May 2014, the Coalition Government introduced a new policy so that prisoners with a history of escape, absconding or serious temporary release failure during the current sentence are prevented from transfer to open conditions, other than in the most exceptional circumstances. There has been only one case satisfying the condition of exceptional circumstances since the policy was implemented. In addition, any prisoner who absconds from an open prison is immediately returned to a higher security prison.</p><p>When the policy was implemented, it was not applied retrospectively. Prisoners already in open conditions were reassessed by senior officials in the National Offender Management Service (NOMS), and any who were assessed as presenting an unacceptable risk in such conditions in light of their previous non-compliance were returned to closed prisons, with the remainder allowed to remain in open conditions because of their compliance with the regime and favourable risk assessment.</p><p>On 4 December 2015, there were 15 prisoners in open prisons who were recorded as having absconded between 1 April 2004 and 21 May 2014 when the policy change came into force.</p><p>Reliable electronic records for absconds and temporary release failures prior to 2004 are not available, therefore only incidents since 2004 could be considered. The data set used here includes prisons classified as having their predominant function to be open. These figures have been drawn from administrative IT systems which, as with any large scale recording system, are subject to possible errors with data entry and processing.</p>",,"Lord Faulks",,"2015-12-22T16:33:31.857Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436559/answer","Biography information for Lord Faulks","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436559/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436559/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-12-09","Prisoner Escapes","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many prisoners who have previously absconded remain in open conditions.","false","Biography information for Lord Falconer of Thoroton",,"Lord Falconer of Thoroton","HL4393"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436560","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-12-22","<p>Foreign criminals who break our laws should be properly punished but not at the expense of the British taxpayer.</p><p>In the last year we have returned more than 5,000 foreign prisoners to their home country. Prisoner transfer agreements are just one way the Government can remove these criminals from the United Kingdom.</p><p>As at 30 September 2015, there were 732 foreign nationals serving a sentence for murder or manslaughter in prisons in England and Wales.</p>",,"Lord Faulks",,"2015-12-22T16:41:57.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436560/answer","Biography information for Lord Faulks","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436560/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436560/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-12-09","Prisoners: Foreign Nationals","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many offenders who are foreign nationals are currently serving a sentence for murder or manslaughter in prisons in England and Wales.","false","Biography information for Lord Falconer of Thoroton",,"Lord Falconer of Thoroton","HL4394"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436561","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-12-22","<p>There is no record of any offender failing to return to prison from temporary release which was authorised to allow them to take driving lessons or tests in the past five years.</p><p /> <p><br> Release on temporary licence is designed to prepare prisoners for their eventual release. Public protection is our priority and all offenders considered for temporary release are fully risk assessed.</p><p /> <p /> <p /> <p>Prisoners are only permitted to take a driving lesson or test if this is required to help their rehabilitation, for example, by improving their employment prospects, thus reducing their likelihood of reoffending.</p><p /> <br />",,"Lord Faulks",,"2015-12-22T16:52:52.44Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436561/answer","Biography information for Lord Faulks","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436561/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436561/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-12-09","Prisoner Escapes","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many prisoners recorded as taking car driving lessons or tests in the last five years absconded or attempted to abscond during a lesson or test.","false","Biography information for Lord Falconer of Thoroton",,"Lord Falconer of Thoroton","HL4395"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436562","Department of Health","false","2015-12-16","<p>The Government reached its decisions on implementing reductions in the 2015/16 local authority public health grant after giving full consideration to its duty under the Equality Act 2010 (the public sector equality duty, or PSED). The Government’s response to a public consultation exercise, published on 4 November 2015, contains an equality analysis of the options for making the saving. A copy is attached.</p><br /><p>Final decisions on the distribution of the grant in 2016/17 have not yet been taken, but again will be made in the light of the PSED. Government decisions on the quantum of the grant have taken account of the PSED. Local authorities are responsible for identifying local needs and priorities for public health interventions, and for making decisions on local spending. Local authorities are themselves subject to the PSED.</p><p><strong></strong></p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2015-12-16T13:30:18.8Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436562/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436562/answer","Local Authority public health grant allocations 201516.pdf","Local Authority Public Health Allocation","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436562/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-12-09","Public Health: Equality","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment has been undertaken to ensure that reductions in the public health budget do not negatively affect those who share protected characteristics under the Equality Act 2010.","false","Biography information for Baroness Gould of Potternewton",,"Baroness Gould of Potternewton","HL4396"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436563","Department of Health","false","2015-12-17","<p>Decisions on local public health spending are a matter for local authorities. Local authorities are mandated to commission open access contraceptive services that provide advice on, and reasonable access to, a broad range of contraceptive substances and appliances.</p><br />",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2015-12-17T17:14:09.92Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436563/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436563/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436563/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-12-09","Contraceptives","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether an assessment has been undertaken of the effect on contraceptive services of reductions in the public health budget.","false","Biography information for Baroness Gould of Potternewton",,"Baroness Gould of Potternewton","HL4397"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436564","Department for Education","false","2015-12-21","<p>A public consultation on reformed content for politics AS and A level closed on 15 December. The proposed new content for politics A level will require all students to study core political theories. This is an improvement on the current system which does not require students to study any political ideologies, including feminism.</p><br /><p>We are analysing the responses to the consultation and have started work with the exam boards to develop the content in light of the views expressed. We will listen carefully to the views of the sector and the wider public as part of this full consultation process.</p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2015-12-21T17:13:56.58Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436564/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436564/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436564/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-12-09","Politics: GCE A-level","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether the suffragettes and the feminist movement will remain part of the new Politics A-level syllabus.","false","Biography information for Baroness Gould of Potternewton",,"Baroness Gould of Potternewton","HL4398"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436565","Department for Transport","false","2015-12-21","<p>Preston-Blackpool South will get a Sunday service all year round. At present the line shuts down for a period in the winter, but from Dec 2017 at least an alternate-hours service will operate all year round. Colne-Preston will get a full hourly Sunday service – twice as many trains on Sunday compared to now, and with the entire Northern fleet being refurbished, passengers will notice rolling stock improvements across the franchise.</p><br /><p>Accrington and Blackburn stations will become Northern Connect stations so will be staffed from 6am to 10pm (if they don’t already have staffing hours longer than this), with WiFi and catering outlets. All Northern stations with more than 10 passengers per day will have ticket machines, real-time information and help points.</p><br /><p>Beyond that there is a franchise wide, £38m investment in bringing stations up to standard, with benefits for many stations, which includes new platform seating, replacement shelters, new waiting rooms and toilets, and customer information screens.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2015-12-21T12:45:54.49Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436565/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436565/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436565/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-12-09","Railways: Lancashire","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what improvements will take place under the new Northern Rail franchise on the Blackpool South and Preston to Colne service, other than the replacement of the Pacer trains.","false","Biography information for Lord Greaves",,"Lord Greaves","HL4399"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436566","Department for Transport","false","2015-12-21","<p>There is no such requirement in the new Northern Franchise Agreement. As the Pacers are owned by two Rolling Stock Companies, any future use is for them to decide.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2015-12-21T12:21:13.84Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436566/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436566/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436566/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-12-09","Rolling Stock: North of England","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether it is a requirement of the new Northern Rail franchise that the Pacer trains that will be withdrawn from service in the North of England will be scrapped or whether they can be redeployed elsewhere.","false","Biography information for Lord Greaves",,"Lord Greaves","HL4400"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436567","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-01-06","<p>The Government announced on 17 December 2015, <em>Official Report</em>, Column 2238-2241, that Local Authorities with social care responsibilities will be able to increase their council tax by up to 2% above the core referendum principles of 2% (4% in total) which is expected to raise an extra £2billion by 2019/20. A breakdown of the £2billion, by how much individual local authorities could raise, has been made and can be viewed at the following link or in the attached document.</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/486708/Core_spending_power_supporting_information.xlsx" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/486708/Core_spending_power_supporting_information.xlsx</a></p><br />",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2016-01-06T14:37:37.07Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436567/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436567/answer","HL4401.xlsx","Supporting Table","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436567/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-12-09","Council Tax","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is the expected yield of an increase of two per cent in the council tax levied by each local authority with adult social care responsibilities, and in each case how much that is per (1) head of population, and (2) number of households.","false","Biography information for Lord Greaves",,"Lord Greaves","HL4401"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436568","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-12-16","<p>The flexibility is not being offered to districts, and so we have not calculated figures for a hypothetical difference. Councils, including non-metropolitan districts, can set any council tax increase they like. If the increase is above the threshold approved by the House of Commons, they must obtain the consent of their local electorate in a referendum.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2015-12-16T16:28:00.487Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436568/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436568/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436568/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-12-09","Council Tax","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Baroness Williams of Trafford on 8 December (HL3988), what is the expected difference, in each county, between an increase of two per cent of the council tax levied by counties in two-tier areas, and the same increase in total if levied by both the counties and all the districts in each of those counties.","false","Biography information for Lord Greaves",,"Lord Greaves","HL4402"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436569","Department for Education","false","2015-12-21","<p>A public consultation on reformed content for politics AS and A level closed on 15 December. The proposed new content for politics A level will require all students to study core political theories. This is an improvement on the current system which does not require students to study any political ideologies, including feminism.</p><br /><p>We are analysing the responses to the consultation and have started work with the exam boards to develop the content in light of the views expressed. We will listen carefully to the views of the sector and the wider public as part of this full consultation process.</p><br /><p>Exam boards will continue to set the detailed content of qualifications.</p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2015-12-21T17:13:21.803Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436569/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436569/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436569/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-12-09","Politics: GCE A-level","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what are the reasons for removing the study of feminism and gender equality from the A-level Politics curriculum.","false","Biography information for Lord Lester of Herne Hill",,"Lord Lester of Herne Hill","HL4403"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436570","HM Treasury","false","2015-12-23","<br /><p>HM Revenue &amp; Customs does not disclose communications it has with its enforcement partners, or the content of those communications, to avoid compromising sensitive policy and operational activities.</p><br />",,"Lord O'Neill of Gatley",,"2015-12-23T10:23:32.43Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436570/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Neill of Gatley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436570/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436570/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-12-09","Electronic Commerce: VAT","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord O’Neill of Gatley on 8 December (HL3854), what were the dates of the last three written communications from HMRC to Trading Standards about VAT fraud among online traders operating from abroad, including email, and to what persons at what offices they were addressed.","false","Biography information for Lord Lucas",,"Lord Lucas","HL4404"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436571","Department of Health","false","2015-12-17","<p>The specific information requested is not available as the Healthy Start Issuing Unit records numbers of applications, rather than numbers of individuals claiming, and an individual or family can make more than one claim for Healthy Start within a year.</p><br /><p>The following table outlines the number of applications received each year since the scheme was started and is made up of the number of claims/applications per year.</p><p>The Healthy Start Scheme initially started in Devon and Cornwall and was rolled out United Kingdom-wide in November 2006.</p><p><strong></strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Financial Year</p></td><td><p>Number of applications/claims</p></td><td><p><br></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2005-06</p></td><td><p>2,445</p></td><td><p>Healthy Start Scheme introduced initially in Devon and Cornwall</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2006-07</p></td><td><p>104,920</p></td><td><p>Extended United Kingdom wide in November 2006</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2007-08</p></td><td><p>197,388</p></td><td><p><br></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2008-09</p></td><td><p>298,077</p></td><td><p><br></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2009-10</p></td><td><p>338,113</p></td><td><p><br></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010-11</p></td><td><p>316,711</p></td><td><p><br></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>320,043</p></td><td><p><br></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>316,277</p></td><td><p><br></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>271,244</p></td><td><p><br></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>226,805</p></td><td><p><br></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015-16 (Up to 15 November)</p></td><td><p>132,633</p></td><td><p><br></p></td></tr></tbody></table><br />",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2015-12-17T17:17:51.597Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436571/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436571/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436571/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-12-09","Healthy Start Scheme","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many pregnant women, new mothers, and children under four have applied to the Healthy Start scheme in each year since that scheme started.","false","Biography information for Baroness Miller of Chilthorne Domer",,"Baroness Miller of Chilthorne Domer","HL4405"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436572","Department of Health","false","2015-12-21","<p>Parents receive health and lifestyle advice, including advice on diet, weight control and physical activity, from their health visitor as part of the Healthy Child Programme.</p><br /><p>For parents, the Government provides online advice on maternal nutrition via the NHS Choices website and the Start4Life website.</p><br /><p>The Your Pregnancy and Baby guide on NHS Choices includes information about a healthy diet in pregnancy. Start4Life produce a range of information booklets with advice for parents, including Healthy Habits for Baby and You which provides information and advice on eating healthily and exercise in pregnancy.</p><p>The Government’s statutory Healthy Start scheme aims to provide a nutritional safety net to the most nutritionally vulnerable pregnant women, new mothers and children under four years old in low income families. The scheme provides vouchers for basic healthy foods (milk, fresh and frozen fruit and vegetables) and infant formula milk. This encourages healthy eating the scheme covers approximately half a million pregnant women, new mothers, and children under four years old in low income families throughout the United Kingdom.</p><br /><p>We currently have no plans to extend the current dietary advice given to pregnant women and new mothers.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2015-12-21T12:20:31.663Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436572/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436572/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436572/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-12-09","Pregnancy: Nutrition","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what further steps they plan to take to improve the diet of pregnant women and new mothers.","false","Biography information for Baroness Miller of Chilthorne Domer",,"Baroness Miller of Chilthorne Domer","HL4406"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436573","Department of Health","false","2015-12-21","<p>The most recent assessment of the influence of poor maternal diet on later health consequences, including the risk of chronic disease in adulthood, was carried out for government by the Scientific Advisory Committee on Nutrition (SACN) in 2011.</p><p>Taking into account the international evidence base and the findings from the United Kingdom National Diet and Nutrition Surveys showing that women of childbearing age are not meeting dietary recommendations, SACN concluded that there is cause for concern. It advised that improving the nutritional status of women of childbearing age, infants and young children, has the potential to improve the health of future generations.</p><p>Current dietary advice to women of reproductive age, those planning a pregnancy and those who are pregnant, is promoted via the NHS Choices website as well as the government’s social marketing campaigns, such as Start4Life.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2015-12-21T17:00:08.66Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436573/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436573/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436573/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-12-09","Pregnancy: Nutrition","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the implications of a poor maternal diet in pregnancy for the life chances of babies, in the light of research conducted in the last decade.","false","Biography information for Baroness Miller of Chilthorne Domer",,"Baroness Miller of Chilthorne Domer","HL4407"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436574","Department for International Development","false","2015-12-18","<p>Supporting robust indicators for Sustainable Development Goal 5.2 on violence against women and girls is critical. DFID is working with international partners including the Global Partnership for Sustainable Development Data to support the development of strong indicators and the development of rigorous, available national data that will enable measurement of progress to end violence against women and girls of all ages.</p>",,"Baroness Verma",,"2015-12-18T13:03:01.35Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436574/answer","Biography information for Baroness Verma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436574/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436574/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-12-09","Developing Countries: Females","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, in the light of global demographic change in which almost 24 per cent of women globally are aged 50 and over, what steps they are taking to ensure that sustainable development goal indicators on violence against women specifically include women over the age of 49, and to ensure that those women are not excluded from reporting mechanisms in the future.","false","Biography information for Baroness Northover",,"Baroness Northover","HL4408"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436575","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-12-21","<p>The Government currently has no plan to revise or update the Agricultural Land Classification Survey guidelines, but will keep their suitability under review.</p><br />",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2015-12-21T14:43:06.18Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436575/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436575/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436575/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-12-09","Agriculture: Land","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government when they next intend to revise or update the Agricultural Land Classification Survey guidelines.","false","Biography information for Lord Patten",,"Lord Patten","HL4409"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436576","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-12-17","<p>The Maldives is an Islamic country. Under its laws public observance of any religion other than Islam is prohibited. We state this in our Travel Advice and advise UK tourists to respect local traditions, customs, laws and religions at all times.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2015-12-17T15:42:52.863Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436576/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436576/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436576/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-12-09","Maldives: Religious Freedom","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is their assessment of the freedom of Christian worship by British citizens visiting the Maldives.","false","Biography information for Lord Patten",,"Lord Patten","HL4410"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436577","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-12-17","<p>It is our understanding that British citizens are not hindered from Christian worship in Turkey. As stated in the EU Commission’s Annual Progress Report on Turkey released on 10 November, freedom of worship continues to be generally respected.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2015-12-17T15:43:14.4Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436577/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436577/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436577/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-12-09","Turkey: Religious Freedom","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is their assessment of the freedom of Christian worship afforded to British citizens visiting Turkey.","false","Biography information for Lord Patten",,"Lord Patten","HL4411"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436578","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-12-17","<p>The current state of the Syrian civil war makes it difficult to offer explicit protection to Syrian minorities. The Assad regime creates the conditions for extremism in Syria by prosecuting a war it cannot win, destroying communities and the social fabric of the country. The only way to secure the position of Syria’s minority communities is to find a political solution to the crisis.</p><p>However, the International Syria Support Group has agreed that protecting the rights of all Syrians, regardless of ethnicity or religious domination is fundamental. The UK will continue to work with this, as political discussions continue.</p><p>The UK also supports non-governmental efforts to promote dialogue between different ethnic and sectarian groups in Syria, as we seek further progress on a political settlement. Minorities including Alawites, Christians, Druze, Kurds and Turkmen have been represented in these projects.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2015-12-17T15:29:50.667Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436578/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436578/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436578/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-12-09","Syria: Religious Freedom","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is their strategy for the continued protection of Alawites, Christians and Druze in the areas of Syria now controlled by the government of President Assad.","false","Biography information for Lord Patten",,"Lord Patten","HL4412"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436579","Department for Transport","false","2015-12-21","<p>Network Rail currently has no funded strategic plans for significant upgrading on this route. However, it advises that it is working closely with local stakeholders, including Local Enterprise Partnerships and local authorities, to work up potential schemes that could support growth and meet the needs of passengers.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2015-12-21T12:25:54.55Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436579/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436579/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436579/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-12-09","London-Exeter Railway Line","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether the annual amount spent on upgrading the railway tracks and stations between Salisbury and Exeter between 2015 and 2020 will increase or decrease in real terms.","false","Biography information for Lord Patten",,"Lord Patten","HL4413"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436580","Department of Health","false","2015-12-16","<p>The health and social care needs of older prisoners will continue to be managed through health needs assessments (HNAs). HNAs address these needs on a prison-by-prison basis, reflect the diverse health needs of prisoners, including older prisoners, and identify the health needs which inform health commissioning in that establishment.</p><br /><p>Public Health England, NHS England and the National Offender Management Service commission individual HNAs in all prisons in England on a regular basis, as part of the commissioning timetable.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2015-12-16T14:04:19.257Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436580/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436580/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436580/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-12-09","Health Services: Prisoners","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government when they plan to produce a national strategy plan for the health and care of older prisoners.","false","Biography information for Lord Bradley",,"Lord Bradley","HL4414"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436581","Department for Transport","false","2015-12-21","<p>The Government has now lifted the restriction on direct, scheduled, commercial air services between Sierra Leone and the UK. The Department is aware of one company that has applied for, and been issued, a Foreign Aircraft Operating Permit by the Civil Aviation Authority to operate services between Sierra Leone and the UK.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2015-12-21T12:28:44.663Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436581/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436581/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436581/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-12-09","Aviation: Sierra Leone","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon on 26 November (HL3704), whether they have completed their review of the possibility of resuming direct flights to Sierra Leone, and if so, whether they are currently processing any permissions for flights to begin.","false","Biography information for Baroness Hayman",,"Baroness Hayman","HL4415"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436582","Department for International Development","false","2015-12-18","<p>The majority of the Independent Commission for Aid Impact (ICAI) commissioners’ air and rail journeys and hotels are booked in advance by the ICAI secretariat through DFID’s internal travel system to ensure value for money in line with DFID/ICAI guidance. These invoices are then verified and settled by the Secretariat. In the minority of cases where travel cannot be booked in advance, commissioners pay up-front and their submitted expense claims with receipts are then verified by the Head of the Secretariat and reimbursed.</p>",,"Baroness Verma",,"2015-12-18T13:12:26.11Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436582/answer","Biography information for Baroness Verma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436582/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436582/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-12-09","Independent Commission for Aid Impact","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether Commissioners of the Independent Commission for Aid Impact receive funding to cover travel and hotel expenses ahead of visits, or whether they are reimbursed for meeting those costs personally.","false","Biography information for Lord Myners",,"Lord Myners","HL4416"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436583","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-12-21","<p>The Government has made no assessment of the progress made by the Metropolitan Police in establishing out of court disposal scrutiny panels. We are working with PCCs to ensure there are appropriate scrutiny arrangements in place.</p>",,"Lord Faulks",,"2015-12-21T16:10:34.947Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436583/answer","Biography information for Lord Faulks","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436583/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436583/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-12-09","Alternatives to Prosecution: Greater London","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the progress made by the Metropolitan Police in introducing out-of-court-disposal scrutiny panels for youth and adult crime across Greater London.","false","Biography information for Lord Ponsonby of Shulbrede",,"Lord Ponsonby of Shulbrede","HL4417"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436584","Department of Health","false","2015-12-21","<p>The Chief Executive of NHS England, Simon Stevens, is not a civil servant and it is for him to take decisions on invitations received. There are no plans to issue guidance to NHS England.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2015-12-21T12:59:36.073Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436584/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436584/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436584/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-12-09","NHS England","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Prior of Brampton on 9 December (HL4036), what assessment they have made of whether it is appropriate for the Chief Executive of NHS England to take part in a political debate programme, and of whether doing so is consistent with the requirement for senior public servants to remain politically neutral; and whether they plan to issue new guidance to NHS England on the basis of that assessment.","false","Biography information for Lord Scriven",,"Lord Scriven","HL4418"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436585","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-12-22","<p>Devolution is bottom-up and led by local areas; proposals are developed by local partners and constitute part of a formal negotiation with the Government. During negotiations, a number of options were discussed with Sheffield City Region, including the Greater Manchester model. The final agreement has been published on the gov.uk website.</p><br />",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2015-12-22T12:52:08.58Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436585/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436585/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436585/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-12-09","Devolution: Sheffield","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether, in the process of its devolution deal, Sheffield City Region asked for, or was offered, the same powers as Manchester, either for its governance arrangements or for the devolution of powers and monies.","false","Biography information for Lord Scriven",,"Lord Scriven","HL4419"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436586","Department for International Development","false","2015-12-21","<p>As of 8th December the UN estimate that more than 920,000 refugees and migrants have crossed the Mediterranean to Europe this year. Almost 770,000 have arrived in Greece, and a further 150,000 have arrived in Italy. A large number of refugees remain in the Middle East. The most accurate figures are available for Syrian refugees, of whom there currently are 2,181,293 in Turkey, 1,070,189 in Lebanon, 632,762 in Jordan, and 244,527 in Iraq. Additionally, 2,117,361 Palestinian refugees are currently registered in Jordan, and 452,669 in Lebanon. It is also estimated that North Africa is host to 234,901 refugees, the majority of whom are in Egypt (187,753) and Libya (36,984).</p>",,"Baroness Verma",,"2015-12-21T14:27:52.07Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436586/answer","Biography information for Baroness Verma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436586/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436586/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-12-09","Refugees","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what estimate they have made of the number of refugees in (1) Europe, (2) the Middle East, and (3) North Africa, and what those figures are broken down by country.","false","Biography information for Lord Selkirk of Douglas",,"Lord Selkirk of Douglas","HL4420"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436587","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-12-22","<p>My Department does not publish forecasts of net additions.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford","HL4422 ; HL4423 ; HL4424","2015-12-22T12:52:42.233Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436587/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436587/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436587/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-12-09","Housing","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is their estimate of the net change in the number of homes in the UK between May 2015 and May 2020.","false","Biography information for Lord Shipley",,"Lord Shipley","HL4421"
