"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436591","Department for International Development","false","2015-12-21","<p>The biggest impediments to Palestinian economic progress are the Israeli-imposed movement and access restrictions. The current movement and access restrictions relating to Gaza are leading to a stagnated economy and worsening situation for the people living there. An improved economy is not only essential for the people of Gaza, but is firmly in Israel’s security interests. We have consistently called on Israel to improve movement and access into and out of Gaza, including extending operating times at Kerem Shalom and will continue to do so.</p>",,"Baroness Verma",,"2015-12-21T14:26:59.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436591/answer","Biography information for Baroness Verma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436591/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436591/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-12-09","Israel: Gaza","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they have assessed the humanitarian impact of increasing the capacity of the Kerem Shalom goods crossing between Israel and Gaza; and whether they have plans to discuss that issue with the government of Israel.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL4425"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436592","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-12-16","<p>While we have not discussed this issue with the Israeli authorities, we remain deeply concerned about restrictions on freedom of movement in the Occupied Palestinian Territories. Our Ambassador in Tel Aviv raised the issue of freedom of movement with Israeli National Security Advisor Cohen on 2 November. Our Consul-General to Jerusalem also raised this issue with the Mayor of Jerusalem on 28 October.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2015-12-16T14:00:35.803Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436592/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436592/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436592/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-12-09","Israel: Palestinians","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they have discussed, or have any plans to discuss, with the government of Israel, the impact of exit permit restrictions on inhabitants of Gaza and the West Bank who seek medical treatment elsewhere.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL4426"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436593","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-12-16","We are aware of the construction of the anti-tunnel canal and of reports of a potential risk of salt-water infiltration into agricultural land in the surrounding area. We will continue to monitor the situation.",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2015-12-16T14:24:41.397Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436593/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436593/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436593/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-12-09","Egypt: Gaza","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they have any plans to discuss with the government of Egypt the risk of salt-water infiltration into the agricultural land of the Gaza Strip resulting from the newly-constructed anti-tunnel canal.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL4427"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436594","Home Office","false","2015-12-21","<p>Asylum seekers and refugees have access to health services and if they raise torture as part of their asylum claim, they are signposted to organisations that specialise in providing support for torture survivors.</p><p>We have no current plans to increase the number of places available under the Gateway Protection programme. The responsibility for identifying and referring refugees to the UK rests with the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees. We will continue to work closely with them to identify those in most need of protection.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2015-12-21T15:25:24.497Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436594/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436594/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436594/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-12-09","Refugees","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what steps they are taking to ensure that torture survivors who reach the UK, in particular those from Syria, have access to specialist rehabilitation; and whether they have plans to increase the number of places available via the Gateway Protection Programme for torture survivors from all states.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL4428"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436595","Northern Ireland Office","false","2015-12-23","<p>I have nothing further to add to my earlier responses.</p>",,"Lord Dunlop",,"2015-12-23T09:52:17.987Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436595/answer","Biography information for Lord Dunlop","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436595/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436595/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2015-12-09","Northern Ireland Government","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answers by Lord Dunlop on 27 November (HL3723) and 8 December (HL4130), whether those answers include all security personnel who served in Northern Ireland but are not from Northern Ireland.","false","Biography information for Lord Laird",,"Lord Laird","HL4429"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436597","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-01-21","<p>We have not undertaken a formal consultation. This clause will receive full Parliamentary scrutiny during the Bill's passage through Parliament.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2016-01-21T12:23:41.333Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436597/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436597/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436597/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-12-09","Public Sector: Trade Unions","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what consultation they carried out about prohibiting public sector employers from providing a check-off service.","false","Biography information for Lord Mendelsohn",,"Lord Mendelsohn","HL4431"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436598","Cabinet Office","false","2015-12-23","<p>The prohibition on deduction of union subscriptions from wages in the public sector (check-off) is being considered in an impact assessment to be published in due course.</p>",,"Lord Bridges of Headley",,"2015-12-23T15:23:50.947Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436598/answer","Biography information for Lord Bridges of Headley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436598/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436598/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-12-09","Public Sector: Trade Unions","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what impact assessment they conducted on provisions in the Trade Union Bill prohibiting public sector employers from providing a check-off service.","false","Biography information for Lord Mendelsohn",,"Lord Mendelsohn","HL4432"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436599","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-12-15","<p>In March 2015 DECC published a report by AECOM titled ‘An Assessment of the Costs, Performance, and Characteristics of UK Heat Networks’. The report included a review of the prices charged to final customers by a representative sample of heat networks (7 in total). The average heat price was found to be 6.43p/kWh but with a wide range of 4.64 to 9.88 p/kWh reflecting differences in network design, construction, commissioning and operation. On average this is less than the modelled cost of gas central heating in flats and terraced houses when boiler ownership costs are included (7.22 to 10.24p/kWh).</p><br /><p>The Government is aware that costs to the consumer can vary and achieving cost savings is dependent on the quality of the individual network. DECC has supported industry development of a technical code of practice for heat networks, and worked closely with industry and consumer groups on the development of Heat Trust, an independent consumer protection scheme that launched in November 2015. There are also plans to launch an on-line cost comparator tool in 2016 to allow a consumer to assess their charges against gas central heating. This greater transparency of heat charges is complemented by the billing information requirements in the Heat Network (Metering and Billing) Regulations 2014.</p><br />",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2015-12-15T15:48:46.477Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436599/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436599/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436599/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-12-09","District Heating","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they have made any assessment of the cost of energy bills to people served by District Heating Networks.","false","Biography information for Lord Black of Brentwood",,"Lord Black of Brentwood","HL4433"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436600","Department for Transport","false","2015-12-22","<p>Section 170 of the Road Traffic Act 1988 requires a driver to stop and report an accident involving horses, cattle, sheep, asses, mules, pigs, goats or dogs, but not cats or wild animals. This requirement arises from their status as working animals rather than as domestic pets.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2015-12-22T11:37:09.28Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436600/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436600/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436600/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-12-09","Roads: Accidents","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon on 30 November (HL3685), on what basis they differentiate dogs and cats in the requirements to report accidents.","false","Biography information for Lord Black of Brentwood",,"Lord Black of Brentwood","HL4434"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436601","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-12-17","<p>We announced on 12 October that the permitted development right for the change of use from office to residential will be made permanent. We further announced that the rights will in future provide for an office to be demolished and replaced on a like-for-like basis as residential. The details of the rights including any requirements about the use, eligibility criteria and any matters for prior approval, including in relation to demolition and replacement, will be provided in due course.</p><p><br></p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford","HL4436","2015-12-17T11:59:35.94Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436601/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436601/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436601/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-12-09","Change of Use","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether, before 13 November, the B1 planning class remained a requirement for offices that also qualified for a residential planning designation.","false","Biography information for Lord Campbell-Savours",,"Lord Campbell-Savours","HL4435"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436602","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-12-17","<p>We announced on 12 October that the permitted development right for the change of use from office to residential will be made permanent. We further announced that the rights will in future provide for an office to be demolished and replaced on a like-for-like basis as residential. The details of the rights including any requirements about the use, eligibility criteria and any matters for prior approval, including in relation to demolition and replacement, will be provided in due course.</p><p><br></p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford","HL4435","2015-12-17T11:59:35.847Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436602/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436602/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436602/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-12-09","Change of Use","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, where an office property that qualified for a residential planning designation is demolished, whether any restrictions are placed on the building of a new property on that land according to the former office property’s footprint.","false","Biography information for Lord Campbell-Savours",,"Lord Campbell-Savours","HL4436"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436603","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-12-17","<p>Unfair parking fines push up the cost of living and undermine the high street. Local authorities should be making it easier to park to support local shops, local jobs and tourism by increasing footfall. Making parking more difficult stifles local trade, driving motorists into the arms of internet retailers and out of town superstores.</p><p>Existing legislation clearly restricts the purposes for which monies generated from parking may be spent by local authorities to off-street parking, transport and environmental improvements.</p><p>The Local Government Transparency Code 2015 requires local authorities to publish a breakdown of income and expenditure on the authority’s parking account. This includes details of revenue collected from on-street parking, off-street parking and Penalty Charge Notices and a breakdown of how the authority has spent a surplus on its parking account.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2015-12-17T15:23:14.393Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436603/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436603/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436603/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-12-09","Parking Offences: Fines","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government on what local authorities are permitted to spend profits from parking enforcement after covering enforcement costs; and what assessment they have made of how much such profit local authorities make from such enforcement.","false","Biography information for Lord Bradshaw",,"Lord Bradshaw","HL4437"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436624","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-12-18","<p>The recognition of foreign honours is a matter for the Royal Prerogative and is governed by convention, rather than by law.</p>","Rochford and Southend East","James Duddridge",,"2015-12-18T14:25:13.837Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436624/answer","Biography information for James Duddridge","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436624/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436624/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-12-09","Honours","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what the legal position is on the use of prefixes or styles granted by virtue of honours in Commonwealth realms in the UK to (a) either to a citizen of a Commonwealth realm and (b) to a dual national who is also national of Great Britain and Northern Ireland; how such honours are recognised; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","19412"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436626","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-12-14","<p>It is our intention that the independent Institute for Apprenticeships (IfA) will be established by April 2017. The Institute will approve apprenticeship standards and safeguard apprenticeship quality.</p><br /><p>The body will not be responsible for the operational functions associated with funding of apprenticeships and the administration of the levy. These will be fulfilled by the Government’s operational agencies.</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2015-12-14T14:36:03.647Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436626/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436626/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436626/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-12-09","Apprentices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what the relationship will be between the new Institute for Apprentices and the industry-led body that will administer the Apprenticeships Levy.","false","Biography information for Peter Kyle","Hove","Peter Kyle","19485"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436628","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-12-14","<p>Skills policy is a devolved area so the devolved administrations will continue to have control over how to support businesses through training and apprenticeships.</p><br /><p>We are working closely with the Welsh Government and other devolved administrations to ensure they get their fair share of the levy and can work out how best to use it to complement their own apprenticeships and skills policies.</p><br /><p>We will engage with skills ministers in the devolved administrations, including Julie James AC/AM, to do all we can to make the levy work for employers and would-be apprentices across the UK.</p><br />","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2015-12-14T14:19:26.357Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436628/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436628/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436628/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-12-09","Apprentices: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what recent discussions he has had with the devolved administrations on the distribution and use of funds raised by the proposed Apprenticeship Levy.","false","Biography information for Kevin Brennan","Cardiff West","Kevin Brennan","19462"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436634","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-12-18","<p>Economic growth is the best way to reduce poverty. We are providing opportunity and training for all, so that everyone can secure their own economic future. That might be through setting up their own business and Government has so far backed over 33,500 Start-Up Loans, worth over £180m. There are a record 5.3 million small businesses in the UK.The Mone Review, led by entrepreneur Michelle Mone, is bringing forward recommendations for how best to support entrepreneurship in disadvantaged communities.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2015-12-18T14:51:00.467Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436634/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436634/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436634/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-12-09","Economic Growth","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment he has made of the effect of poverty and inequalities on entrepreneurialism and economic growth.","false","Biography information for Natalie McGarry","Glasgow East","Natalie McGarry","19345"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436635","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-12-14","<p>This data is publicly available and can be found on the ONS website in the ‘Balance of Payments, Quarter 2 (April to June) 2015’.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2015-12-14T16:33:38.937Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436635/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436635/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436635/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-12-09","UK Trade with EU","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, if he will estimate the UK's current trade deficit with the EU.","false","Biography information for Mr Peter Bone","Wellingborough","Mr Peter Bone","19366"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436637","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-12-18","<p>The Trade in Services Agreement (TiSA) negotiation is ongoing. A full sustainable impact assessment is being conducted on the TISA. The terms of reference of the report include analysis of the impact of the TISA on climate change. The final inception report can be found on the EU’s website.</p><p>The Department for Business, Innovation and Skills has not carried out any additional assessments in relation to the impact of the agreement on wider climate change policies, but works closely with the Department of Energy and Climate Change on the content of the Agreement to ensure it aligns with the UK’s wider policy objectives.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2015-12-18T14:49:45.5Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436637/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436637/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436637/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-12-09","Trade in Services Agreement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment he has made of the implications for implementing his Department's policies for combatting climate change and decarbonising electricity generation of the Trade in Services Agreement.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","19375"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436639","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-12-15","<p>The Government made clear in the Spending Review its commitment to science and research. We will protect science resource funding in real terms from its current level of £4.7 billion per annum for the rest of the Parliament. Growth in the ring fence will be used to invest in a new £1.5 billion Global Challenges Research Fund for UK science to pioneer new ways of tackling global problems. As well as increasing resource spending for science, we are investing in new scientific infrastructure on a record scale, delivering on the £6.9 billion science capital commitment in our manifesto to provide the infrastructure and funding to keep the UK globally competitive.</p><p>The allocation of budgets to individual funding bodies, programmes and facilities has yet to be determined. As per previous spending rounds this allocation process will take place over the coming months.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2015-12-15T14:52:40.08Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436639/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436639/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436639/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-12-09","Science: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what steps the Government is taking to maintain current spending levels on the core elements of the science budget in real terms over the course of the Parliament.","false","Biography information for Mark Durkan","Foyle","Mark Durkan","19387"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436643","Cabinet Office","false","2015-12-14","<p>The restrictions on civil servants’ involvement in political activities are set out in the Civil Service Management Code. This is available at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/418696/CSMC-_April_2015.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/418696/CSMC-_April_2015.pdf</a></p><br />","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2015-12-14T17:34:54.237Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436643/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436643/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436643/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-12-09","Civil Servants: Political Activities","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, whether there is, or has been within the last 10 years, a requirement on (a) applicants to the civil service and (b) civil servants upon entry to the civil service to disclose party political membership.","false","Biography information for Chris Bryant","Rhondda","Chris Bryant","19367"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436644","Cabinet Office","false","2015-12-14","<p>Information about the number, pay bands, and cost of special advisers will be published shortly in the normal way.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2015-12-14T10:56:04.693Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436644/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436644/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436644/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-12-09","Ministerial Policy Advisers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what the total cost to the public purse was of ministerial special advisors in the last financial year; and how much is projected to be so spent in the next financial year.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","19361"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436650","Cabinet Office","false","2015-12-21","<p>The Government Digital Servicehavesupported departments to recruit nearly 200 senior digital and technology experts. Through those appointments, we have helped to establish senior leadership across government that is able to deliver digital and technology transformation.</p><p>They have established strong knowledge and expertise within government to support us to make better technology choices, supported by networks of digital and technology leaders. More broadly, improving the digital skills of the Civil Service is an important and ongoing task.</p><br />","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2015-12-21T10:34:00.4Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436650/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436650/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436650/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-12-09","Electronic Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what plans the Government has to raise the level of skills and technical capability in the civil service to support the Government's digital transformation programme.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","19397"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436652","Cabinet Office","false","2015-12-21","<p>The Government Digital Service will continue to act as the digital centre for government, supporting departments as they conduct their business transformation.They have already created platforms to solve common problems faced across government such as <a href="http://gov.uk/" target="_blank">GOV.UK</a>, the Digital Marketplace and <a href="http://gov.uk/" target="_blank">GOV.UK</a>Verify. In addition they are doing this by establishing Common Technology Services for civil servants - this will deliver new, flexible, common technology, opening up government contracts to more suppliers - saving time and money.</p><p>They are also creatinga payments platform for people to pay government the same way and a platform for digital communications making it easier to be able to message government, track the status of their registrations and applications and receive notifications.</p><br />","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock","19402","2015-12-21T10:35:31.017Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436652/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436652/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436652/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-12-09","Electronic Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what technology platforms and services the Government plans to develop as part of the (a) Government as a Platform and (b) Common Technology Services strategy to support the digital transformation of public services; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","19398"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436654","Cabinet Office","false","2015-12-21","<p><a href="http://gov.uk/" target="_blank">GOV.UK</a>Verify is currently in public beta and is constantly being improved and expanded based on user feedback. The current demographic coverage is 80%.</p><p>It is now possible to verify your identity using a wide range of evidence, including any passport, any EU identity document, and any bank account or payment card.</p><br />","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2015-12-21T10:32:58.487Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436654/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436654/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436654/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-12-09","Electronic Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what progress has been made on the GOV.UK Verify programme; and what plans the Government has to develop it further in the future.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","19399"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436656","Cabinet Office","false","2015-12-18","<p>The Government is committed to improving the way in which data is used and shared between public bodies for the benefit of the citizen, including the use of digital technology to transform public services in a way that is efficient, cost-effective and safe. The Government Digital Service will continue to support public bodies in making the most appropriate use of data and in ensuring that robust safeguards are in place to protect the privacy of individuals. We will continue to encourage public bodies to make non-sensitive administrative and aggregate data available as Open Data, as part of our ongoing commitment to transparency. We have also developed a <a href="https://data.blog.gov.uk/2015/12/08/data-science-ethics/" target="_blank">draft ethical framework</a>(which can be accessed at: <a href="https://data.blog.gov.uk/2015/12/08/data-science-ethics/" target="_blank">https://data.blog.gov.uk/2015/12/08/data-science-ethics/</a>) for how the Government uses data and we are embarking on a public dialogue which will understand and explore public opinion on the opportunities presented by data science</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2015-12-18T10:29:33.85Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436656/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436656/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436656/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-12-09","Public Sector: Data Protection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what recent assessment has been made of people's attitudes towards public bodies using and sharing their data with other parts of the public sector as part of digitally transformed public services; and what plans the Government has to build trust and assurance among people on the Government's use of their data as part of those public services.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","19400"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436657","Cabinet Office","false","2015-12-21","<p>The Government Digital Service will continue to act as the digital centre for government, supporting departments as they conduct their business transformation.They have already created platforms to solve common problems faced across government such as <a href="http://gov.uk/" target="_blank">GOV.UK</a>, the Digital Marketplace and <a href="http://gov.uk/" target="_blank">GOV.UK</a>Verify. In addition they are doing this by establishing Common Technology Services for civil servants - this will deliver new, flexible, common technology, opening up government contracts to more suppliers - saving time and money.</p><p>They are also creatinga payments platform for people to pay government the same way and a platform for digital communications making it easier to be able to message government, track the status of their registrations and applications and receive notifications.</p><br />","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock","19398","2015-12-21T10:35:31.077Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436657/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436657/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436657/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-12-09","Government Digital Service","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how the £450 million funding allocated to the Government Digital Service in the Spending Review and Autumn Statement 2015 will be spent; and what the priorities for the Government Digital Service will be over the next (a) 12 and (b) 24 months.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","19402"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436659","HM Treasury","false","2015-12-16","<p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) is making significant progress in preparing for the end of the Aspire IT contract in 2017. In August, HMRC announced that the changes it has planned will ultimately enable the Department to make savings of up to 24 per cent on its £800m annual IT budget by 2020-21, while maintaining consistent delivery of services to customers.</p><br /><p>Through its <em>Building Our Future</em> programme, HMRC is continuing to engage with its people and trade unions about the way in which it is transforming, including the way in which it is equipping operations with the modern IT services and platforms they need to run effectively. Currently, there are no plans to hold a formal consultation on the end of the Aspire contract.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2015-12-16T16:21:30.807Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436659/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436659/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436659/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-12-09","Revenue and Customs: ICT","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what plans he has to procure the replacement for the HM Revenue and Customs IT Aspire contract; what consultation there will be with HM Revenue and Customs staff and their representatives; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","19419"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436661","HM Treasury","false","2015-12-14","<p>As the Chancellor announced in the House on 9 December, the government is creating a new Community Recovery Scheme to support households and businesses affected by the floods in Cumbria and Lancashire.</p><br /><p>The Barnett Formula has been applied to this funding in the normal way, and the Northern Ireland Executive will receive £1.322 million in additional funding.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2015-12-14T17:37:39.047Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436661/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436661/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436661/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-12-09","Floods: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what the Barnet consequentials for Northern Ireland are of the £50 million additional funding for flood relief; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Baroness Ritchie of Downpatrick","South Down","Ms Margaret Ritchie","19478"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436663","HM Treasury","false","2015-12-16","<p>Care services provided by certain bodies are subject to a mandatory VAT exemption under EU VAT rules.</p><br /><p>EU VAT rules do not allow the introduction of any new zero rates without the unanimous agreement of all 28 Member States on the basis of a proposal from the Commission.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2015-12-16T16:30:25.883Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436663/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436663/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436663/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-12-09","Carers: VAT","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will make an assessment of the potential merits of changing the VAT status of care providers to zero-rated in order to assist them in meeting the cost of complying with the national living wage.","false","Biography information for Julian Sturdy","York Outer","Julian Sturdy","19492"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436665","HM Treasury","false","2015-12-14","<p>Government proposals regarding reducing the cost of politics were published in the Spending Review 2015.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2015-12-14T17:36:36.003Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436665/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436665/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436665/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-12-09","Political Parties: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to the Autumn Statement and Spending Review 2015, paragraph 1.309, whether any reduction is planned in (a) Cranborne money and (b) Representative money.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","19449"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436666","HM Treasury","false","2015-12-14","<p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) operates a dedicated Severe Weather helpline to offer help and advice on any tax matters to those people and businesses affected by the recent flooding. The helpline is 0800 904 7900</p><p>Opening hours are Monday to Friday, 8.00 am to 8.00 pm; Saturday and Sunday, 8.00 am to 4.00 pm, excluding bank holidays.</p><br /><p>HMRC will also:</p><ul><li>consider instalment arrangements where customers are unable to pay as a result of the floods;</li><li>agree a practical approach when individuals and businesses have lost vital records to the floods;</li><li>suspend debt collection proceedings for those affected by the floods; and</li><li>cancel penalties when the customer has missed statutory deadlines due to the floods. <br><p>The helpline is in addition to other HMRC telephone contact numbers.</p><p><br> <br></li></ul>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","19457 ; 19458","2015-12-14T17:28:59.943Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436666/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436666/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436666/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-12-09","Floods: Cumbria","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether he plans to offer deadline extensions for tax due by businesses affected by flooding in Cumbria.","false","Biography information for Mr Jamie Reed","Copeland","Mr Jamie Reed","19456"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436667","HM Treasury","false","2015-12-14","<p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) operates a dedicated Severe Weather helpline to offer help and advice on any tax matters to those people and businesses affected by the recent flooding. The helpline is 0800 904 7900</p><p>Opening hours are Monday to Friday, 8.00 am to 8.00 pm; Saturday and Sunday, 8.00 am to 4.00 pm, excluding bank holidays.</p><br /><p>HMRC will also:</p><ul><li>consider instalment arrangements where customers are unable to pay as a result of the floods;</li><li>agree a practical approach when individuals and businesses have lost vital records to the floods;</li><li>suspend debt collection proceedings for those affected by the floods; and</li><li>cancel penalties when the customer has missed statutory deadlines due to the floods. <br><p>The helpline is in addition to other HMRC telephone contact numbers.</p><p><br> <br></li></ul>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","19456 ; 19458","2015-12-14T17:29:00.007Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436667/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436667/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436667/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-12-09","Floods: Cumbria","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will introduce an instalment scheme to allow businesses in Cumbria affected by flooding to spread tax payments.","false","Biography information for Mr Jamie Reed","Copeland","Mr Jamie Reed","19457"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436670","HM Treasury","false","2015-12-17","<p>Illegal fuel seized by HMRC is rendered into burning oil by contractors who are approved waste oil recyclers.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2015-12-17T14:11:50.273Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436670/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436670/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436670/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-12-09","Fuels: Seized Articles","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what the practice of HM Revenue & Customs is to deal with illegal fuel seized by that body.","false","Biography information for Danny Kinahan","South Antrim","Danny Kinahan","19310"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436672","HM Treasury","false","2015-12-16","<p>The restriction to finance cost relief brings the rate of relief available for individual landlords more in line with that of corporate landlords.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2015-12-16T16:33:04.167Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436672/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436672/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436672/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-12-09","Mortgages: Interest Rates","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether it is his policy that the changes to interest rate relief on buy-to-let mortgages announced in the Summer Budget 2015 apply to purchasers within a limited company structure.","false","Biography information for Thangam Debbonaire","Bristol West","Thangam Debbonaire","19312"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436674","HM Treasury","false","2015-12-14","<p>I refer the Honourable Member to the answer I gave on December 7th. <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2015-12-01/18395/" target="_blank">http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2015-12-01/18395/</a></p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2015-12-14T17:22:03.483Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436674/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436674/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436674/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-12-09","Revenue and Customs: Dundee","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether the Government plans to relocate all 650 HM Revenue & Customs jobs at Sidlaw House, Dundee, to the Department for Work and Pensions.","false","Biography information for Chris Law","Dundee West","Chris Law","19322"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436675","HM Treasury","false","2015-12-14","<p>The government has made no assessment of the effect on jobs in Dundee as result of the Spending Review and Autumn Statement 2015. A number of economic policies which affect jobs are devolved to the Scottish Government.</p><br /><p>The government has set out its commitment to have the highest employment rate in the G7 and the Autumn Statement set out further measures to support people into work, including extending Jobcentre Plus support to 1.3 million additional claimants on Universal Credit by 2020, and a real terms increase in funding to support people with disabilities and health conditions find, and remain in, work.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2015-12-14T17:34:50.343Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436675/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436675/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436675/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-12-09","Employment: Dundee","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will make an assessment of the potential effect on jobs in Dundee of the policies outlined in the Spending Review and Autumn Statement 2015.","false","Biography information for Chris Law","Dundee West","Chris Law","19323"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436676","HM Treasury","false","2015-12-14","<p>As anounced in the Autumn Statement the UK is recognised as the number one country for attracting infrastructure investment by Nabarro LLP’s 2015 infrastructure index. Nabarro ranks the UK as the top infrastructure investment destination based on its “chart-topping” sustainability and innovation, one of the highest scores for private participation, and strong credit and stability. The report also highlighted the government’s devolution policy as helping to facilitate a favourable investment environment.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2015-12-14T17:35:49.577Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436676/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436676/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436676/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-12-09","Infrastructure: Investment","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what the evidential basis is for his contribution of 25 November 2015, Official Report, column 1366, that Britain topped the league table of the best places in the world to invest in infrastructure.","false","Biography information for Seema Malhotra","Feltham and Heston","Seema Malhotra","19333"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436677","HM Treasury","false","2015-12-15","<p>HM Revenue and Customs do not collect business rates. Information on VAT receipts by industry or trade is not held.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2015-12-15T13:09:36.13Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436677/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436677/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436677/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-12-09","Gun Sports: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what progress HM Revenue and Customs has made in recovering VAT and business rates from the shooting industry in the last five years.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Mr Mark Hendrick","19371"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436678","HM Treasury","false","2015-12-16","<p>Since the scheme’s inception in April 2013, 12 charities that fall within Wakefield postcodes have claimed back Gift Aid on their small cash donations.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2015-12-16T16:31:43.977Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436678/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436678/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436678/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-12-09","Charities: Wakefield","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many charities registered in Wakefield constituency have claimed back Gift Aid on small cash donations using the Gift Aid Small Donation Scheme since that scheme's inception.","false","Biography information for Mary Creagh","Wakefield","Mary Creagh","19380"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436679","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-12-17","<p>The Glasgow and Clyde Valley City Deal is progressing well. Local partners are committed to a programme of 20 infrastructure projects over twenty years. The Glasgow and Clyde Valley Cabinet are agreeing business cases, with construction work to begin in due course.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2015-12-17T15:48:50.977Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436679/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436679/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436679/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-12-09","Local Government: Glasgow","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what progress is being made on the Glasgow and Clyde Valley City Deal.","false","Biography information for Philip Boswell","Coatbridge, Chryston and Bellshill","Phil Boswell","19381"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436680","HM Treasury","false","2015-12-18","<p>HMRC does not have specific figures for disposing of illegal fuel.</p><p /> <p>HMRC fights fraud on a wide range of fronts, from special units performing thousands of roadside checks to raiding laundering plants. The UK has recently announced, jointly with Ireland, an improved new marker for rebated fuel, which will make it much harder to launder marked fuel and sell it at a profit.</p><br />","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2015-12-18T12:08:59.763Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436680/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436680/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436680/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-12-09","Fuels: Smuggling","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what the cost to the Exchequer was of disposing of illegal fuel in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Danny Kinahan","South Antrim","Danny Kinahan","19377"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436682","HM Treasury","false","2015-12-14","<p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) operates a dedicated Severe Weather helpline to offer help and advice on any tax matters to those people and businesses affected by the recent flooding. The helpline is 0800 904 7900</p><p>Opening hours are Monday to Friday, 8.00 am to 8.00 pm; Saturday and Sunday, 8.00 am to 4.00 pm, excluding bank holidays.</p><br /><p>HMRC will also:</p><ul><li>consider instalment arrangements where customers are unable to pay as a result of the floods;</li><li>agree a practical approach when individuals and businesses have lost vital records to the floods;</li><li>suspend debt collection proceedings for those affected by the floods; and</li><li>cancel penalties when the customer has missed statutory deadlines due to the floods. <br><p>The helpline is in addition to other HMRC telephone contact numbers.</p><p><br> <br></li></ul>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","19456 ; 19457","2015-12-14T17:29:00.067Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436682/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436682/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436682/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-12-09","Floods: Cumbria","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what support his Department is offering to businesses affected by flooding in Cumbria in advance of tax payment deadlines.","false","Biography information for Mr Jamie Reed","Copeland","Mr Jamie Reed","19458"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436683","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-12-17","<p>Through the Housing and Planning Bill we are taking measures to tackle rogue landlords who rent out sub-standard accommodation. Our proposals include a database of rogue landlords and property agents, introducing banning orders for serious or repeat offenders, a tougher fit and proper person test, extending Rent Repayment Orders and introducing civil penalties for offences such as failing to comply with an improvement notice or overcrowding a property<strong>. <br></strong><br>In addition, over the last Parliament, we made over £6.7 million available to local authorities to help them tackle rogue landlords in their areas. We have also invited 65 local authorities to bid for a share of a further £5 million funding to tackle rogue landlords and will be announcing successful schemes shortly.</p><br />","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2015-12-17T17:02:57.13Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436683/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436683/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436683/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-12-09","Private Rented Housing: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what steps he is taking to tackle landlords who knowingly rent out unsafe and substandard accommodation.","false","Biography information for Steve Rotheram","Liverpool, Walton","Steve Rotheram","19317"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436684","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-01-26","<p>The Government is committed to increasing the number of first time buyers. Action taken in support of this Includes:</p><p>- extending the Right to Buy - which has supported council tenants into home ownership for decades - to housing association tenants. This will give another 1.3 million families the chance to purchase a home at right to buy level discounts;</p><p>- Help to Buy schemes, targeting those wanting to get onto the housing ladder with 80% of sales going to first time buyers, which have so far enabled over 130,000 families to purchase a home;</p><p>- launching, on 1 December 2015, the Help to Buy: ISA which will help first-time buyers save for their first deposit. The Government will top up savings by 25%, up to a maximum top-up of £3,000; and</p><p>- a £2.3 billion fund to deliver 200,000 Starter Homes by 2020, to be exclusively offered to first time buyers under 40 at a 20% discount on market value.</p><p>Information on housing tenure and the age of the household reference person in England, based on data from DCLG’s English Housing Survey, can be found (in Annex Table 1.4) at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/469214/2013-14_Section_1_Households_tables_and_figures_FINAL.xlsx" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/469214/2013-14_Section_1_Households_tables_and_figures_FINAL.xlsx</a></p><br />","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-01-26T14:54:47.697Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436684/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436684/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436684/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-12-09","Owner Occupation: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what assessment he has made of trends in the number of young people who own their own home since 2010.","false","Biography information for Steve Rotheram","Liverpool, Walton","Steve Rotheram","19318"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436685","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-12-18","<p>The Department has made no such formal assessment. The Social Housing Regulator for England's Regulatory Framework only applies to registered providers of social housing in England. Responsibility for housing is a devolved matter.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2015-12-18T09:38:01.773Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436685/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436685/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436685/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-12-09","Social Rented Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what assessment he has made of the extent of financial and operational links between the social housing sector in Scotland and England.","false","Biography information for Natalie McGarry","Glasgow East","Natalie McGarry","19344"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436686","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-12-15","<p>Many local authorities are choosing to reduce street lighting at night to save energy costs and reduce carbon emissions using a variety of approaches, which include replacing traditional sodium lamps with more energy efficient LED lamps.</p><p>However, decisions about street lighting are for elected local councillors, reflecting local circumstances and views.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2015-12-15T15:53:59.213Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436686/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436686/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436686/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-12-09","Roads: Lighting","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what encouragement he has given local authorities to switch street lighting to LED light sources since May 2015.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","19297"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436688","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-12-14","<p>This information is not held centrally by this Department.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2015-12-14T17:15:20.307Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436688/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436688/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436688/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-12-09","Vacant Land: Planning Permission","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many planning refusals for greenfield sites have been overturned on appeal in each year between 2010 to 2015.","false","Biography information for Mr Douglas Carswell","Clacton","Mr Douglas Carswell","19305"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436692","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-12-14","<p>Average rents for supported housing are provided by private registered providers to the Homes and Communities Agency’s Statistical Data Return. This is available at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/statistical-data-return-statistical-releases" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/statistical-data-return-statistical-releases</a></p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2015-12-14T17:14:55.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436692/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436692/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436692/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-12-09","Supported Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what the average weekly rent and service charge for supported accommodation including (a) foyers, (b) direct access hostels, (c) supported housing for older people and (d) other supported housing has been in each (i) region and (ii) local authority area in the last three years.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","19465"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436693","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-12-16","<p>I recently wrote to the betting industry to underline the importance that the government attaches to the existing voluntary agreements between betting and greyhound racing through which funding is provided towards areas including animal welfare.</p><p>The Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs (Defra) is currently undertaking a review of the effectiveness of the Welfare of Racing Greyhounds Regulations 2010. In addition, the Environment, Food and Rural Affairs (EFRA) Parliamentary Select Committee is undertaking an inquiry into greyhound welfare to feed into Defra’s review. My Department has submitted written evidence to EFRA and we will want to consider any recommendations put forward by them as part of Defra’s review of the 2010 Regulations.</p><br />","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2015-12-16T17:03:19.067Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436693/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436693/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436693/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-12-09","Greyhound Racing: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, whether his Department plans to establish a statutory levy on greyhound racing to help support the welfare of retired greyhounds.","false","Biography information for Angela Smith","Penistone and Stocksbridge","Angela Smith","19491"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436695","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-12-14","<p>The Government is keen to encourage all local authorities to look at how they work more effectively and efficiently with services providers and partner organisations in their area to ensure that their residents receive high quality and cost effective services.</p><p>I am aware of the progress made by Kettering Borough Council in this area including the significant savings made and increased customer satisfaction and I am happy to encourage other authorities to look at its customer service centre as an example of good practice.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2015-12-14T17:16:45.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436695/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436695/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436695/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-12-09","Kettering Borough Council: Information Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will encourage the use of the customer services centre at Kettering Borough Council as an example of good practice for other local authorities to follow.","false","Biography information for Mr Philip Hollobone","Kettering","Mr Philip Hollobone","19477"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436696","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-12-14","<p>All of the£129 million clawback funding that has been announced by BT is available to the local authorities to support additional roll-out, subject to suitable deployment opportunities being identified which ensure value for money.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-12-14T15:47:20.387Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436696/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436696/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436696/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-12-09","Broadband","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what proportion of the total declared claw back from BT under National Broadband Scheme contracts has been reallocated to local authorities for additional roll-out under the Scheme.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","19470"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436697","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-12-14","<p>Thanks to the way we have constructed the contracts, BT has announced £129 million of clawback funding. This is available to the local authorities to support further broadband deployment without any additional funding being added to it by either the government or by the local authorities.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-12-14T15:37:49.597Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436697/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436697/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436697/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-12-09","Broadband","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what additional funding allocations have been provided to each local authority as a result of declared claw back from BT under the National Broadband Scheme.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","19471"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436698","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-12-15","<p>With support from Government, and by working directly with police forces across the UK, the gambling industry is committed to tackling and reducing crime and bringing those who commit crimes against shop staff, customers and property to justice.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2015-12-15T11:53:35.55Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436698/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436698/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436698/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-12-09","Gaming Machines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what steps he is taking to assist bookmakers in reducing (a) crime on their premises and (b) the incidence of malicious damage to fixed odds betting terminals.","false","Biography information for Carolyn Harris","Swansea East","Carolyn Harris","19331"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436699","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-12-17","<p>All betting shop operators are required by the Gambling Commission’s Licence Conditions and Code of Practice to have social responsibility policies and processes in place. In addition, the industry trade body the Association of British Bookmakers (ABB) has a mandatory code of conduct in place, which is reviewed regularly to evaluate its effectiveness.</p><p>I have explained to the industry that I expect them to demonstrate that they are improving existing player protection initiatives and evaluating the effects of previous initiatives. As I said at the recent RGT harm minimisation conference, government and industry should never feel that there is an end point to social responsibility. Industry owes a duty of care to its customers.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2015-12-17T15:46:13.067Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436699/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436699/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436699/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-12-09","Bookmakers: Codes of Practice","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, if he will make an assessment of whether the Code of Conduct for bookmakers is meeting the aims for which it was drawn up.","false","Biography information for Carolyn Harris","Swansea East","Carolyn Harris","19332"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436700","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-12-15","<p>The Government, along with the Gambling Commission, is in the process of evaluating the effects of ending unsupervised stakes over £50 and I hope to publish the results early in the new year.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2015-12-15T11:49:59.913Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436700/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436700/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436700/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-12-09","Gaming Machines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, with regard to fixed odds betting terminals, what steps are being taken to (a) ensure that the player protection measures introduced from April 2015 are effectively evaluated and (b) independently assess whether the £50 threshold for supervised play is set at an effective level.","false","Biography information for Carolyn Harris","Swansea East","Carolyn Harris","19328"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436701","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-01-28","<p>The two one-off grants to MG Alba were provided to support the production of high-quality Gaelic language content, including original drama, and to continue its valued services for Gaelic speakers.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-01-28T15:37:19.817Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436701/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436701/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436701/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-12-09","MG Alba: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, with reference to the contribution of the Minister of State for Culture and the Digital Economy of 3 December 2015, Official Report, column 510, what the purpose was of the two one-off grants paid to MG Alba.","false","Biography information for Margaret Ferrier","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Margaret Ferrier","19385"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436702","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-12-14","<br /><p>68 Brimstone missile weapon releases occurred during Operation HERRICK.</p><p>A detailed statistical breakdown by year is contained in Table four of the publication: Op HERRICK (Afghanistan) Aircraft Statistics dated 29 October 2015 available at the following link: https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/operation-herrick-afghanistan-aircraft-statistics</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2015-12-14T16:31:45.483Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436702/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436702/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436702/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-12-09","Afghanistan: Peacekeeping Operations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many strikes were made using the Brimstone missile during Operation HERRICK.","false","Biography information for Douglas Chapman","Dunfermline and West Fife","Douglas Chapman","19368"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436703","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-12-15","<br /><p>There are currently 40 Remotely Piloted Aircraft System pilots in the Royal Air Force.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2015-12-15T16:27:43.827Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436703/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436703/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436703/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-12-09","Unmanned Air Vehicles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many remotely piloted aircraft system pilots are employed in the RAF; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","19382"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436704","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-12-14","<br /><p>As announced in Strategic Defence and Security Review (SDSR) 2010 we can extend the life of the existing Vanguard class submarines into the early 2030s. Cost estimates for supporting the ballistic missile submarines during the transition from Vanguard to Successor are not materially affected by minor changes to scheduled dates.</p><br />","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2015-12-14T16:35:05.573Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436704/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436704/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436704/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-12-09","Trident Submarines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, pursuant to the Answer of 30 November 2015 to Question 17622, if he will identify separately the marginal costs associated with maintaining the Vanguard submarines in service for five years longer then envisaged.","false","Biography information for Alan Brown","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Alan Brown","19334"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436705","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-12-17","<br /><br /><p>The UK has three arrangements with France in support of the Teutates programme. The first is between the UK and French Nuclear Safety regulators to ensure safety of operations, and the second and third are between the Ministry of Defence and the Commissariat l'énergie atomique et aux énergies alternatives (CEA) to support the construction of the Epure facility at Valduc.</p><br /><br />","Sevenoaks","Michael Fallon",,"2015-12-17T16:07:10.227Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436705/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436705/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436705/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-12-09","France: Nuclear Weapons","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, which memoranda of understanding have been agreed with the French government in support of Project Teutates.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","19342"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436706","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-12-17","<br /><p>I am withholding details of such experiments as their disclosure would prejudice national security and could prejudice relations between the United Kingdom and another State.</p>","Sevenoaks","Michael Fallon",,"2015-12-17T16:08:54.32Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436706/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436706/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436706/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-12-09","France: Nuclear Weapons","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many (a) joint Anglo-French and (b) solely French experiments have been conducted using (i) laser and (ii) hydrodynamics facilities at Atomic Weapons Establishment Aldermaston to date.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","19343"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436707","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-12-16","<br /><br /><p>The information is not held in the format requested. However, the table below shows, where available, the estimated number of reserves recruited in Scotland in the last three Financial Years.</p><br /><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Service</strong></p></td><td colspan="3"><p><strong>FINANCIAL YEAR (1 APRIL TO 31 MARCH)</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td></td><td><p><strong>2012-13</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2013-14</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2014-15</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Maritime Reserve</strong></p></td><td><p>See note</p></td><td><p>80</p></td><td><p>100</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Army Reserve</strong></p></td><td><p>480</p></td><td><p>300</p></td><td><p>550</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Royal Air Force Reserve </strong></p></td><td><p>See note</p></td><td><p>70</p></td><td><p>110</p></td></tr></tbody></table><br /><br /><p>Note – information not available.</p><br /><table><tbody><tr><td rowspan="4"><p>The Future Reserves 2020 Volunteer Reserve population includes mobilised Volunteer Reserves, High Readiness Reserves, and those volunteer reserves serving on Full Time Reserve Service and Additional Duties Commitment.</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>The figures are based on Service personnel's stationed location and not their location of residence - where personnel work is not necessarily where they live.</p><br /><br />","Canterbury","Mr Julian Brazier",,"2015-12-16T17:12:45.507Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436707/answer","Biography information for Sir Julian Brazier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436707/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436707/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-12-09","Reserve Forces: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many reserves were recruited in Scotland in (a) 2010-11, (b) 2011-12, (c) 2013-14 and (d) 2014-15.","false","Biography information for Steven Paterson","Stirling","Steven Paterson","19330"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436708","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-12-14","<p>The Ministry of Defence (MOD) Children's Education Advisory Service (CEAS) provides information, advice and support to Service parents on all aspects of the education of their children. CEAS advice is free and impartial, and covers a range of issues including mainstream state schools and special state maintained schools, state boarding schools, the MOD's Queen Victoria School Dunblane, and independent schools both day and boarding. CEAS also advise on MOD educational allowances, and the strict eligibility criteria that must be met.</p><p>CEAS offer tailored support for Service parents who experience difficulty in obtaining the state school of their choice and where necessary support them through the appeal process. As well as help-lines and an email enquiry service, CEAS provide four dedicated peripatetic Parent Support Officers who are educational professionals and cover all locations within the United Kingdom.</p><p>The guidance provided by the MOD was covered in some detail during a House of Commons Defence Committee Inquiry in 2013, and more detail is available in the Fourth Report of Session 2013-14: The Armed Forces Covenant in Action? Part 3: Educating the Children of Service Personnel, which is available in the Library of the House and at the following link:</p><p>http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201314/cmselect/cmdfence/586/58602.htm</p><br />","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2015-12-14T16:21:21.933Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436708/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436708/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436708/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-12-09","Armed Forces: Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what guidance his Department provides to service personnel on choosing state and private schools for their children's education.","false","Biography information for Douglas Chapman","Dunfermline and West Fife","Douglas Chapman","19347"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436709","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-12-16","<p>UK air strikes are conducted in accordance with Rules of Engagement and International Humanitarian Law.The risks of collateral damage or civilian casualties are assessed and mitigated based on intelligence and the use of precision guided weapons. There have been no reports so far of civilian casualties as a result of UK air strikes in Syria.</p><br />","Sevenoaks","Michael Fallon",,"2015-12-16T16:24:40.98Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436709/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436709/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436709/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-12-09","Syria: Military Intervention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what evaluation his Department made of the number and location of civilian workers who work at the al-Omar oil field in Syria before ordering Royal Air Force planes to bomb that facility; and how many civilians have been killed as a result of UK military action on targets in Syria to date.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","19294"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436710","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-12-18","<p>Daesh has obtained weapons through capture, and through the black market. It has also captured a variety of armed and unarmed vehicles. In addition, Daesh has produced its own Improvised Explosive Devices (IEDs), including vehicle-borne IEDs and suicide bombs, improvised rockets, mortars and munitions.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2015-12-18T12:04:30.98Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436710/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436710/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436710/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-12-09","Islamic State","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what assessment he has made of the sources of (a) arms and (b) armed vehicles obtained by Daesh.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","19296"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436711","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-12-14","<br /><p>The Ministry of Defence has several organisations that provide policing and guarding across the defence estate. Our policy is to deploy the Ministry of Defence Police (MDP) at those sites where constabulary powers are needed. We also use Regular Service Personnel or the specialist Military Provost Guard Service who have the ability to be armed where required.</p><p>As part of the 2015 Strategic Defence and Security Review, we are reviewing how we provide our policing and guarding at some sites.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2015-12-14T16:38:58.06Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436711/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436711/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436711/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-12-09","Ministry of Defence: Security","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what assessments he has made of the future security needs of Ministry of Defence (MoD) establishments in the UK; whether responsibility for guarding any MoD sites, assets and infrastructure will be transferred from the MoD Police to the Armed Forces in the next five years; how and when such changes might be decided upon and implemented; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","19461"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436712","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-12-16","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer given to him by my right hon. Friend the Prime Minister on 1 December 2015 to Question 18014.</p>","Sevenoaks","Michael Fallon",,"2015-12-16T16:18:52.987Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436712/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436712/answer","Hansard Extract 1 December 2015.docx HOC 18014.docx","Syria  Armed Conflict","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436712/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-12-09","Syria: Armed Conflict","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, pursuant to his evidence to the Defence Committee on UK military operations in Syria and Iraq on 1 December 2015, HC 657, Q36, if he will publish a breakdown of the groups comprising the estimated 70,000 fighters in Syria described by the UK government as moderate.","false","Biography information for Dr Julian Lewis","New Forest East","Dr Julian Lewis","19490"
