"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436159","HM Treasury","false","2015-12-14","<p>The government has published the policy costing note for the apprenticeship levy on gov.uk. It can be found here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/480565/SRAS2015_policy_costings_amended_page_25.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/480565/SRAS2015_policy_costings_amended_page_25.pdf</a></p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2015-12-14T17:30:45.03Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436159/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436159/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436159/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-12-08","Apprentices: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to paragraph 2.10 of the Spending Review and Autumn Statement 2015, if he will publish the analysis and methodology used to estimate that the proposed apprenticeship levy will raise £3 billion by 2020-21.","false","Biography information for Seema Malhotra","Feltham and Heston","Seema Malhotra","19084"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436160","HM Treasury","false","2015-12-16","<p>Total science resource spending of £4.7 billion will be protected in real terms for the rest of the Parliament.</p><br /><p>Government has also made a long term science capital commitment of £6.9 billion between 2015-2021 to support the UK’s world-class research base.</p><br />","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2015-12-16T17:35:14.057Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436160/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436160/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436160/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-12-08","Science: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether he plans to ring-fence the capital and resource elements of the science budget settlement announced in the Spending Review and Autumn Statement 2015.","true","Biography information for Carol Monaghan","Glasgow North West","Carol Monaghan","19182"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436161","HM Treasury","false","2015-12-16","<p>Treasury Ministers and officials meet regularly with a wide variety of organisations in the public and private sectors as part of the process of policy development and delivery.</p><br /><p>Details of ministerial and permanent secretary meetings with external organisations on departmental business are published on a quarterly basis and are available at:</p><br /><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/hmt-ministers-meetings-hospitality-gifts-and-overseas-travel" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/hmt-ministers-meetings-hospitality-gifts-and-overseas-travel</a></p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2015-12-16T15:58:54.17Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436161/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436161/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436161/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-12-08","Financial Services: Compensation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, when he last met the Financial Conduct Authority to discuss how its uses its powers under section 382 of the Financial Services and Markets Act 2000 to compel a registered firm to compensate investors for losses incurred as a result of that firm's breaches of its statutory obligations; and what the outcome of that meeting was.","false","Biography information for Kirsten Oswald","East Renfrewshire","Kirsten  Oswald","19202"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436162","HM Treasury","false","2015-12-16","<p>Her Majesty’s Treasury does not keep records of cases of investors who have sought compensation from the Financial Services Compensation Scheme.</p><br /><p>The Honourable Member should contact the Financial Services Compensation Scheme directly with inquiries relating to compensation claims.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2015-12-16T16:15:00.677Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436162/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436162/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436162/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-12-08","Financial Services: Compensation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate he has made of the number of and outcomes achieved by (a) Connaught Fund investors and (b) other investors who have sought payment from the Financial Services Compensation Scheme when their independent financial adviser has declared a default on an award of compensation by the Financial Ombudsman's Service; and if he will publish that assessment.","false","Biography information for Kirsten Oswald","East Renfrewshire","Kirsten  Oswald","19204"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436163","HM Treasury","false","2015-12-16","<p>This is a matter for the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA), which is operationally independent from Government.</p><br /><p>This question has been passed on to the FCA. They will reply directly to the Honourable Member by letter. A copy of the letter will be placed in the Library of the House.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","19193 ; 19195 ; 19196 ; 19197 ; 19200 ; 19201","2015-12-16T16:24:22.773Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436163/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436163/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436163/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-12-08","Investment Trusts","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether he is satisfied by the proportion of Connaught Fund investors who received the full level of compensation awarded to them.","false","Biography information for Kirsten Oswald","East Renfrewshire","Kirsten  Oswald","19191"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436164","HM Treasury","false","2015-12-16","<p>The FCA is an independent non-governmental body responsible for regulating and supervising the financial services industry within the framework of statutory objectives and duties agreed by Parliament. Although the Treasury is responsible for setting the legal framework, oversight of business practicesis a matter for the FCA Board.</p><br /><p>The Government appreciates the real difficulties and the serious implications the Connaught issue has had for investors and is following the situation closely.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2015-12-16T15:52:49.253Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436164/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436164/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436164/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-12-08","Investment Trusts","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will encourage the Financial Conduct Authority to bring its investigation into the Connaught Fund to an early conclusion; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Kirsten Oswald","East Renfrewshire","Kirsten  Oswald","19203"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436165","HM Treasury","false","2015-12-16","<p>Treasury Ministers regularly receive advice on regulatory issues.</p><br /><p>As was the case with previous Administrations, it is not the Treasury’s practice to provide details of such advice.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2015-12-16T16:16:33.537Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436165/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436165/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436165/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-12-08","Financial Services: Advisory Services","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, when he last received advice on the adequacy of the Financial Conduct Authority's requirements for professional indemnity to underpin advice given by independent financial advisers; and what action he took in response to that advice.","false","Biography information for Kirsten Oswald","East Renfrewshire","Kirsten  Oswald","19192"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436166","HM Treasury","false","2015-12-16","<p>This is a matter for the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA), which is operationally independent from Government.</p><br /><p>This question has been passed on to the FCA. They will reply directly to the Honourable Member by letter. A copy of the letter will be placed in the Library of the House.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","19191 ; 19195 ; 19196 ; 19197 ; 19200 ; 19201","2015-12-16T16:24:22.837Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436166/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436166/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436166/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-12-08","Investment Trusts","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, when he was first told that Capital Financial Managers Limited knew by September 2009 that investors' funds were exposed to risks not provided for in the information memorandum for the Connaught Fund.","false","Biography information for Kirsten Oswald","East Renfrewshire","Kirsten  Oswald","19193"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436167","HM Treasury","false","2015-12-16","<p>Treasury Ministers and officials receive regular representations on a wide range of issues.</p><br /><p>As was the case with previous Administrations, it is not the Treasury’s practice to provide details of all such discussions.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2015-12-16T15:51:51.637Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436167/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436167/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436167/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-12-08","Financial Services: Compensation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what representations he has received on differences in the (a) criteria used by the Financial Ombudsman's Service and Financial Services Compensation Scheme to determine cases and (b) determinations reached by those bodies.","false","Biography information for Kirsten Oswald","East Renfrewshire","Kirsten  Oswald","19194"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436168","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-12-15","<p>DCLG confirmed at the Spending Review our intention, by the end of this Parliament, to allow local government to keep 100% of the business rates they raise locally. We have had initial discussions with local government representative bodies and individual authorities about the reform programme. We will broaden and deepen those discussions in the New Year.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2015-12-15T15:53:25.233Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436168/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436168/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436168/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-12-08","Non-domestic Rates","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what progress he has made on plans to allow local councils to retain business rates.","false","Biography information for Michael Tomlinson","Mid Dorset and North Poole","Michael Tomlinson","19142"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436169","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-12-15","<p>The Spending Review and Autumn Statement announced that funding of the Temporary Accommodation management fee will be devolved to local authorities from 2017/18, giving them more freedom and flexibility in how they use this funding. Current levels of funding will be maintained and, in addition, councils will receive £10 million a year more. The Department for Communities and Local Government will set out the precise detail of how the new funding will be distributed in 2016/17. The Department will work closely with local authorities and other partners to ensure that funding will be allocated in order to most effectively help councils tackle homelessness.</p><br />","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","18895 ; 18896","2015-12-15T15:42:31.907Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436169/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436169/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436169/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-12-08","Temporary Accommodation: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, with reference to paragraph 1.149 of the Spending Review and Autumn Statement 2015, on what basis the total amount allocated to local authorities for funding temporary accommodation has been calculated.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","19078"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436170","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-12-15","<p><br>The Department does not hold information about the individual rent setting plans of local authorities or housing associations.</p><p>At Budget 2015 the Government announced its intention to reduce rents for housing association and local authority tenants, by 1% a year, for four years, from April 2016. This will help protect social tenants from rising housing costs, whilst protecting taxpayers from rising costs of subsidising rents through housing benefit. We expect local authorities and housing associations to be planning on this basis.</p><br />","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2015-12-15T15:52:11.343Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436170/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436170/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436170/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-12-08","Social Rented Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what information his Department holds on the number of (a) local authorities and (b) housing associations which had planned, prior to the announcement in paragraph 1.125 of the Spending Review and Autumn Statement 2015, to raise rents above any of the relevant local housing allowance rates between 2016 and 2020.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","19079"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436171","Department for Transport","false","2015-12-16","<p>The Blue Badge scheme applies to on-street parking only. The Department for Transport (DfT) has produced non-statutory guidance designed to help local authorities with the administration and enforcement of the scheme. The guidance can be viewed at:</p><br /><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/the-blue-badge-scheme-local-authority-guidance-england" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/government/publications/the-blue-badge-scheme-local-authority-guidance-england</a></p><br /><p>The guidance also includes a link to a good practice guide on inclusive mobility which includes a chapter on parking issues aimed at helping local authorities meet their obligations under the Equalities Act 2010.</p><p><strong></strong></p><br />","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2015-12-16T16:44:13.617Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436171/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436171/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436171/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-12-08","Blue Badge Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what guidance his Department provides for local authorities on the administration of blue badge disabled parking arrangements.","false","Biography information for Michael Tomlinson","Mid Dorset and North Poole","Michael Tomlinson","19143"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436172","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-12-15","<p>Local authorities have played a vital role in helping those Syrian refugees arriving here to settle into a new life in the UK. The Syrian Resettlement Team, made up of officials from Home Office, DCLG and DFID, is working closely with those local authorities that wish to participate in the Syrian Vulnerable Persons Resettlement Scheme, helping to manage the process of accepting refugees for resettlement, providing help and advice where appropriate.</p><p>At the Spending Review the Government committed £129 million to assist with local authority costs over years 2-5 for those local authorities who are resettlling refugees under the Syrian Vulnerable Persons Resettlement Scheme. This is unringfenced funding and it will be for local authorities to decide how to use the funding to support the refugees they resettle.</p><br />","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2015-12-15T15:56:03.203Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436172/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436172/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436172/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-12-08","Refugees: Syria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what help his Department will provide to assist local authorities to resettle Syrian refugees over the next five years.","false","Biography information for Michael Tomlinson","Mid Dorset and North Poole","Michael Tomlinson","19144"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436173","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-12-15","<p>Those who have been granted refugee status or humanitarian protection must qualify under local rules set by the relevant local authority and have sufficient priority under the local authority’s allocation scheme to be eligible for social housing, just as anyone else.</p><p>At the Spending Review the Government committed £129 million to assist with local authority costs over years 2-5 for those local authorities who are resettlling refugees under the Syrian Vulnerable Persons Resettlement Scheme. This is unringfenced funding and it will be for local authorities to decide how to use the funding to support the refugees they resettle.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2015-12-15T15:55:02.123Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436173/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436173/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436173/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-12-08","Housing: Refugees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what recent steps his Department has taken to help councils to house refugees.","false","Biography information for Michael Tomlinson","Mid Dorset and North Poole","Michael Tomlinson","19145"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436174","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-12-14","<p>My hon. Friend, the Parliamentary Under Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, (Baroness Williams of Trafford) attended Chanukah reception at No. 10 in 2015. The former Parliamentary Under Secretary of State for Communities andLocal Government, the former hon. Member for Bristol West (Stephen Williams) attended the Deputy Prime Minister’s Chanukah reception on 18 December 2014 at Admiralty House.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2015-12-14T17:23:28.767Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436174/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436174/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436174/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-12-08","Department for Communities and Local Government: Festivals and Special Occasions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, which Ministers of his Department attended events to celebrate Chanukah in (a) 2014 and (b) 2015.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Mr Mark Hendrick","19174"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436175","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-12-14","<p>Greater Manchester Local Enterprise Partnership’s successful bid for a Life Sciences Enterprise Zone covers two sites in central Manchester.</p><p>Neither site is within Salford and Eccles.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2015-12-14T17:16:01.237Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436175/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436175/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436175/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-12-08","Enterprise Zones: Greater Manchester","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, whether the Greater Manchester Life Science Enterprise Zone will cover the Salford and Eccles constituency.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","19166"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436176","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-12-17","<p>The Government's policy is to work with local areas to deliver effective devolution with the governance necessary to support this. We support the move to create new unitary authorities where such a move is locally driven and enjoys local support.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2015-12-17T15:47:41.637Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436176/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436176/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436176/answer","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436176/answer/previousversion/35361","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-12-08","Local Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what his policy is on creation of new unitary authorities.","false","Biography information for Mr Peter Bone","Wellingborough","Mr Peter Bone","19212"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436177","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-12-14","<p><em>The Energy Efficiency (Private Rented Property)(England and wales) Regulations 2015</em> require that, subject to certain exemptions, domestic and non-domestic private rented sector landlords improve their properties to a minimum energy efficiency rating of E from April 2018.</p><br /><p>The Department is currently developing guidance documents to assist landlords in complying with their obligations under the regulations, and to support enforcement authorities in fulfilling their duties.</p><p><br></p><br />","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2015-12-14T15:05:04.267Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436177/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436177/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436177/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-12-08","Private Rented Housing: Energy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what steps her Department is taking to ensure that landlords in the private rented sector comply with the requirement for properties to be a minimum of energy efficiency rating E by April 2017.","false","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr   Poulter","19268"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436178","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-12-14","<p>The Department for Communities and Local Government does not provide any specific guidance to private registered providers of social housing on energy efficiency of social housing stock. I would expect private registered providers to look at all opportunities for efficiencies.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2015-12-14T17:14:07.393Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436178/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436178/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436178/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-12-08","Social Rented Housing: Energy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what steps he plans to take to require social landlords to improve the energy efficiency of their housing stock.","false","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr   Poulter","19267"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436179","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-12-15","<p>We announced at the Autumn Statement that the Government is supporting development on brownfield land through a £2 billion Long Term Housing Development Fund to unlock housing development for up to 160,000 homes. This funding will support our key manifesto commitments to create a Brownfield Regeneration Fund and to fund Housing Zones to transform brownfield sites into new housing. At least half of the Long Term Fund will be spent on brownfield projects. The Housing Development Fund will be formally launched in the New Year.</p><br />","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2015-12-15T15:51:19.35Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436179/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436179/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436179/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-12-08","Derelict Land","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Answer of 14 September 2015 from the Parliamentary Under-Secretary for Communities and Local Government, on Brownfield Land, Official Report, column 742, when further details of the £1 billion brownfield regeneration fund will be announced; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Julian Sturdy","York Outer","Julian Sturdy","19236"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436180","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-12-15","<p>At the Spending Review the Government committed around £130 million to assist with local authority costs over years 2-5 of the scheme. This will be allocated on a tariff basis over four years, tapering from £5,000 per person in their second year in the UK, to £1,000 per person in year five. There will also be support for education and healthcare, and a special cases fund to assist the most vulnerable refugees.</p><br />","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2015-12-15T15:50:20.777Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436180/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436180/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436180/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-12-08","Refugees: Syria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what financial support his Department plans to provide to local authorities to resettle Syrian refugees in years two to five of the vulnerable persons relocation scheme.","false","Biography information for Michael Tomlinson","Mid Dorset and North Poole","Michael Tomlinson","19243"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436181","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-12-15","<p>Performance enhancing drugs remain a threat to the integrity of sport and the health and wellbeing of all our athletes. The Government supports the work of UK Anti-Doping which works tirelessly to ensure athletes and sport are clean. Through testing programmes, intelligence sharing with law-enforcement agencies on supplying and trafficking, and its excellent athlete education initiatives, UKAD is one of the world's most highly regarded national anti-doping organisations.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2015-12-15T11:51:58.873Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436181/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436181/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436181/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-12-08","Sports: Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what steps his Department is taking to work with sports clubs to discourage young people from taking performance enhancing drugs.","false","Biography information for Craig Whittaker","Calder Valley","Craig Whittaker","19238"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436182","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-12-17","<p>According to Ofcom’s Communications Market Report published in August 2015, superfast broadband coverage was at 78% across the Yorkshire and the Humber region. The full report can be found here -<a href="http://stakeholders.ofcom.org.uk/binaries/research/infrastructure/2015/downloads/connected_nations2015.pdf" target="_blank">http://stakeholders.ofcom.org.uk/binaries/research/infrastructure/2015/downloads/connected_nations2015.pdf</a>.</p><br /><p>As a result of the Government's Superfast Broadband Programme, well over 250,000 Additional homes and businesses now have access to superfast broadband in the Yorkshire and the Humber region.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-12-17T11:49:39.823Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436182/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436182/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436182/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-12-08","Broadband: Yorkshire and the Humber","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what recent progress he has made on the delivery of superfast broadband in the Yorkshire and Humber region.","false","Biography information for Craig Whittaker","Calder Valley","Craig Whittaker","19239"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436183","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-12-14","<p>Performance enhancing drugs remain a threat to the integrity of sport and the health and wellbeing of all our athletes. The Government supports the work of UK Anti-Doping which works tirelessly to ensure athletes and sport are clean. Through testing programmes, intelligence sharing with law-enforcement agencies on supplying and trafficking, and its excellent athlete education initiatives, UKAD is one of the world's most highly regarded national anti-doping organisations</p><p> </p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2015-12-14T15:01:08.69Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436183/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436183/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436183/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-12-08","Sports: Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what assessment he has made of the prevalence of the use of performance drugs among young people in sport.","false","Biography information for Craig Whittaker","Calder Valley","Craig Whittaker","19237"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436184","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-12-14","<p>Ofcom’s Connected Nations Infrastructure Report 2015 states that in May 2015, 79% of homes and businesses in Wales had access to superfast broadband. The full report can be found here -<a href="http://stakeholders.ofcom.org.uk/binaries/research/infrastructure/2015/downloads/connected_nations2015.pdf" target="_blank">http://stakeholders.ofcom.org.uk/binaries/research/infrastructure/2015/downloads/connected_nations2015.pdf</a></p><p>The Government’s programme to deliver superfast broadband has ensured that so far more than 504,000 additional homes and businesses in Wales now have access to superfast broadband, which would not have been reached commercially, following almost £67 million of contracted Government funding.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-12-14T17:14:11.2Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436184/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436184/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436184/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-12-08","Broadband: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what proportion of (a) homes and (b) businesses in Wales have access to superfast broadband.","false","Biography information for Vernon Coaker","Gedling","Vernon Coaker","19273"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436185","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-12-14","<p>Ofcom’s Connected Nations Infrastructure Report 2015 states that in May 2015, 73% of homes and businesses in Scotland had access to superfast broadband. The full report can be found here -<a href="http://stakeholders.ofcom.org.uk/binaries/research/infrastructure/2015/downloads/connected_nations2015.pdf" target="_blank">http://stakeholders.ofcom.org.uk/binaries/research/infrastructure/2015/downloads/connected_nations2015.pdf</a>.</p><p>The Government’s programme to deliver superfast broadband has ensured that so far more than 356,000 additional homes and businesses in Scotland now have access to superfast broadband, which would not have been reached commercially, following investment of over £100 million of contracted Government funding.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-12-14T17:16:51.843Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436185/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436185/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436185/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-12-08","Broadband: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what proportion of (a) homes and (b) businesses in Scotland have access to superfast broadband.","false","Biography information for Vernon Coaker","Gedling","Vernon Coaker","19274"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436186","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-12-14","<p>Ofcom’s Connected Nations Infrastructure Report 2015 states that in May 2015, 83% of homes and businesses in England had access to superfast broadband. The full report can be found here -<a href="http://stakeholders.ofcom.org.uk/binaries/research/infrastructure/2015/downloads/connected_nations2015.pdf" target="_blank">http://stakeholders.ofcom.org.uk/binaries/research/infrastructure/2015/downloads/connected_nations2015.pdf</a>.</p><p>The Government’s programme to deliver superfast broadband has ensured that so far more than 2.4 million additional homes and businesses in England now have access to superfast broadband, which would not have been reached commercially, following well over £313 million of contracted Government funding.</p><br />","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-12-14T17:18:44.62Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436186/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436186/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436186/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-12-08","Broadband","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what proportion of (a) homes and (b) businesses in England have access to superfast broadband.","false","Biography information for Vernon Coaker","Gedling","Vernon Coaker","19275"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436187","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-01-06","<p>DCMS encourages applications from candidates with the widest range of backgrounds. We work closely with Cabinet Office to identify potential barriers to appointments, and put in place a number of actions to overcome them.</p><br /><p>The following statistics are a breakdown of new appointments made by DCMS. Candidates are not required to answer questions about gender, race, sexual orientation or disability - many do not. The stats provided are for candidates who have chosen to disclose this information. Therefore this data is only a snapshot and cannot be used as an accurate representation of our diversity statistics.</p><p><br> <br></p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="4"><p><strong>Gender</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><br></p></td><td><p>Male</p></td><td><p>Female</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015 – 16 (Q1 and Q2)</p></td><td><p>19</p></td><td><p>11</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014 - 15</p></td><td><p>22</p></td><td><p>22</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013 - 14</p></td><td><p>29</p></td><td><p>21</p></td></tr></tbody></table><br /><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="4"><p><strong>Ethnicity</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><br></p></td><td><p>White</p></td><td><p>BAME</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015 – 16 (Q1 and Q2)</p></td><td><p>24</p></td><td><p>-</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014 - 15</p></td><td><p>33</p></td><td><p>3</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013 - 14</p></td><td><p>45</p></td><td><p>4</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><br></p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="4"><p><strong>Disability Status</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><br></p></td><td><p>Yes</p></td><td><p>No</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015 – 16 (Q1 and Q2)</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p><br></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014 - 15</p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>32</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013 - 14</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p><br></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><br></p><p><strong>The information providedis a breakdown ofallappoi