ecretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, pursuant to the Answer of 8 December 2015 to Question 18148, if he will provide a breakdown of public appointments by his Department its executive agencies and non-governmental bodies by (a) gender, (b) ethnicity, (c) socio-economic group, (d) sexual orientation and (e) disability status in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","19257"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436188","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-12-14","<p>Ofcom’s Connected Nations Infrastructure Report 2015 states that in May 2015, 77% of homes and businesses in Northern Ireland had access to superfast broadband. The full report can be found here -<a href="http://stakeholders.ofcom.org.uk/binaries/research/infrastructure/2015/downloads/connected_nations2015.pdf" target="_blank">http://stakeholders.ofcom.org.uk/binaries/research/infrastructure/2015/downloads/connected_nations2015.pdf</a>.</p><p>The Government’s programme to deliver superfast broadband has ensured that so far more than 18,000 additional homes and businesses in Northern Ireland now have access to superfast broadband, which would not have been reached commercially, following over £11.4 million of contracted Government funding.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-12-14T17:20:14.527Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436188/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436188/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436188/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-12-08","Broadband: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what proportion of (a) homes and (b) businesses in Northern Ireland have access to superfast broadband.","false","Biography information for Vernon Coaker","Gedling","Vernon Coaker","19276"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436189","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-12-14","<p>The £230m is BT expenditure and would therefore be in addition to receipts recorded on the BT annual accounts.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-12-14T15:30:18.433Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436189/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436189/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436189/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-12-08","Broadband: Rural Areas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, pursuant to the Answer of 9 November 2015 to Question 13628, whether the £230 million spend incurred by BT is an addition to the £683 million recorded as state aid receipts in BT's accounts.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","19214"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436190","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-12-14","<p>I attended the Reception for Festival of Chanukah - Mr Speaker's annual celebration to mark the Festival of Chanukah, on Wednesday 17th December 2014.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-12-14T15:35:25.3Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436190/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436190/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436190/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-12-08","Judaism: Festivals and Special Occasions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, which Ministers of his Department attended events to celebrate Chanukah in (a) 2014 and (b) 2015.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Mr Mark Hendrick","19173"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436191","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-12-14","<p>DCMS have recently gone through a detailed spending review process which has recognised the enormous value of investing in sport, resulting in an excellent settlement for Sport England. Earlier this year we consulted on plans for a new strategy for sport which will be published shortly and which sets a clear direction for future grassroots sport funding</p><p> </p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2015-12-14T14:21:15.48Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436191/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436191/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436191/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-12-08","Sports: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what recent assessment his Department has made of the adequacy of grassroots sports funding; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","19124"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436192","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-12-14","<p>I hope to publish the evaluation early in the new year.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2015-12-14T14:58:56.613Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436192/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436192/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436192/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-12-08","Gaming Machines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, pursuant to the Answer of 7 December 2015 to Question 18388, when he expects to publish the results of the Government's evaluation of the effects of ending unsupervised stakes above £50 on fixed odds betting terminals in betting shops.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","19215"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436193","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-12-14","<p>The National Tennis Centre (NTC) at Roehampton is a privately funded enterprise owned by the Lawn Tennis Association.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2015-12-14T14:57:21.113Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436193/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436193/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436193/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-12-08","Tennis: Roehampton","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, whether the Government (a) has made or (b) plans to make any contribution to the cost of (i) the construction and (ii) the running of the National Tennis Centre at Roehampton.","false","Biography information for Toby Perkins","Chesterfield","Toby Perkins","19159"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436194","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-12-15","<p>Government recognises the importance of deaf sport to those who take part at both grassroots and elite level. Sport England is investing £365,872 in UK Deaf Sport between 2014 and 2017 in recognition of this.Questions of official recognition at an international level are a matter for the International Olympic Committee.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2015-12-15T11:55:10.087Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436194/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436194/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436194/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-12-08","Deaflympics","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, if he will take steps to ensure that the Deaflympics are recognised as equal to the Olympic and Paralympic Games.","false","Biography information for Lucy Frazer","South East Cambridgeshire","Lucy Frazer","19190"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436195","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-12-15","<p>The Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport has not had any discussions with the London Legacy Development Corporation (LLDC) about EU state aid rules and the West Ham United Football Club contract. The contract relating to West Ham United Football Club's use of the Olympic Stadium is between the West Ham and the LLDC.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2015-12-15T11:59:47.807Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436195/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436195/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436195/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-12-08","West Ham United Football Club: Sportsgrounds","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, whether he has had discussions with the London Legacy Development Corporation about EU state aid rules and West Ham United Football Club's occupancy of the Olympic Stadium.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","19080"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436196","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-12-14","<p>Sport makes a huge contribution to the UK economy, attracting participants and visitors from the UK and abroad.</p><p>The value of sport and physical activity tothe UK economy is estimated at around £40 billion each year, or nearly 3% of UKGross Value Added.Sport related consumer spending was worth around £30 billion in 2012 - over £1 billion of this comes from spending on spectator sports.</p><br /><p>Visit Britain's study on Football Tourism found that total spending by international visitors who attended a football match was £684 million in 2014. Visitors who attended a match had an average spend on average £855 in the UK, compared with an average spend of £628 for those who did not attend a match.</p><p><br>The latest Sport Satellite Account which details these figures can be found at :<a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/450258/UK_Sport_Satellite_Account__2011_and_2012.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/450258/UK_Sport_Satellite_Account__2011_and_2012.pdf</a>.</p><p><br>Visit Britain's study can be found via this link:<a href="https://www.visitbritain.org/sites/default/files/vb-corporate/Documents-Library/documents/2015-9%20VisitBritain%20Report_Football%20tourism%20scores%20for%20Britain.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.visitbritain.org/sites/default/files/vb-corporate/Documents-Library/documents/2015-9%20VisitBritain%20Report_Football%20tourism%20scores%20for%20Britain.pdf</a></p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2015-12-14T14:43:15.473Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436196/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436196/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436196/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-12-08","Sports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what research his Department has conducted or commissioned on the economic benefit of major sports teams to local economies; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","19083"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436197","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-12-14","<p>I refer the honourable member to the written response given in UIN number 14483 on 16th November 2015.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2015-12-14T14:55:01.95Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436197/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436197/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436197/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-12-08","Bookmakers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, if he will make an assessment of the effectiveness of the self-exclusion pilot schemes introduced by bookmakers in Medway and Glasgow.","false","Biography information for Carolyn Harris","Swansea East","Carolyn Harris","19094"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436198","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-12-16","<p>The government, along with Gambling Commission colleagues, are in the process of evaluating the regulations which came into force in April this year which required customers in bookmakers to interact either over the counter or via account based play in order to stake over £50. The last triennial review of stakes and prizes was in 2013, and the findings of the evaluation will inform the timing of the start of the next review.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2015-12-16T17:00:50.197Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436198/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436198/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436198/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-12-08","Gaming Machines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, when the next Triennial Review of Gaming Machine Stake and Prize Limits will begin.","false","Biography information for Carolyn Harris","Swansea East","Carolyn Harris","19093"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436199","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-12-16","<p>As part of the SDSR and our plans for Joint Force 2025 we are investing more than £178 billion in buying and maintaining equipment over the next decade. This includes the modernisation and investment in our air transport fleet which will include the C17, A400M, Voyager and C130J platforms. We are still developing our plans for how the Army's new strike brigades will be deployed, but part of the extra capability we expect them to offer is the ability to deploy at pace by air, sea or to self-deploy over land.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2015-12-16T17:11:54.05Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436199/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436199/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436199/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-12-08","Armed Forces: Deployment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what steps his Department is taking to ensure that there is sufficient lift capacity to airlift the two new strike brigades to theatres of operation.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","19099"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436200","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-12-15","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer given to the hon. Member for Romford (Andrew Rosindell) to Question 13408 on 30 October 2015.</p>","Sevenoaks","Michael Fallon",,"2015-12-15T16:26:29.477Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436200/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436200/answer","Hansard 30 October 2015 HOC 13408.docx","Defence Expenditure","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436200/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-12-08","Defence: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what representations the UK has made to other NATO member states on committing two per cent of their gross domestic product to defence.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","19098"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436201","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-12-14","<p>The Defence Footprint Strategy examines the Defence Estate across the UK, with the aim of providing a smaller more sustainable estate in support of military capabilities. Work to identify the sites which may be released to enable the reduction of the estate through the Footprint Strategy will conclude in 2016, contributing to the Government's commitment to release public sector land for house building during this Parliament.</p><br />","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2015-12-14T16:20:16.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436201/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436201/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436201/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-12-08","Ministry of Defence: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, with reference to paragraph 4.62 in the Strategic Defence and Security Review, published on 23 November 2015, what areas his Department plans to sell to reduce the size of the built estate by 30 per cent; and by what process those areas were chosen.","false","Biography information for Steven Paterson","Stirling","Steven Paterson","19188"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436202","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-12-15","<br /><p>The Ministry of Defence is developing a Footprint Strategy to enable the reduction of its built estate by 30% by 2040. This Strategy is currently being developed and is due to be published in 2016. It is therefore too soon to state what scale of efficiencies might be achieved from our intended estate rationalisation.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2015-12-15T16:22:45.2Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436202/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436202/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436202/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-12-08","Ministry of Defence: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, with reference to paragraph 4.62 in the Strategic Defence and Security Review, published on 23 November 2015, what projection he has made of the savings to the public purse from the sale of 30 per cent of the built estate.","false","Biography information for Steven Paterson","Stirling","Steven Paterson","19189"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436203","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-12-15","<br /><p>As stated in the Spending Review 2015 the Ministry of Defence (MOD) expects to generate £1 billion through the disposal of sites in the financial years 2016-17 to 2020-21.</p><p>The MOD does not disclose annual breakdowns due to the potential for prejudice to its commercial interests.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2015-12-15T16:23:37.55Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436203/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436203/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436203/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-12-08","Ministry of Defence: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, with reference to paragraph 4.62 in the Strategic Defence and Security Review, published on 23 November 2015, what estimate he has made of the revenue that will be received from the sale of 30 per cent of the built estate.","false","Biography information for Steven Paterson","Stirling","Steven Paterson","19187"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436204","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-12-16","<br /><p>A range of reports are generated on the material state of all Royal Navy submarines. Given the broad range of reporting that is undertaken and the large range of highly complex engineering systems reported on, this information is not held centrally and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2015-12-16T16:25:17.387Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436204/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436204/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436204/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-12-08","Astute Class Submarines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many reports have been made on the assessed material state of HMS (a) Astute, (b) Ambush and (c) Artful.","false","Biography information for Steven Paterson","Stirling","Steven Paterson","19185"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436205","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-12-15","<br /><p>Under the deployment plan the Ministry of Defence and police have identified a range of security tasks that the military will undertake in order to release police firearms officers to respond to a major counter-terrorism (CT) incident. A proportion of these are in Scotland although we do not reveal the specific numbers of personnel involved for reasons of operational security.</p><p>The plan also allows us to generate a far more significant surge of military personnel to deploy in response to a major CT incident. These personnel deploy across the UK, including in Scotland. Military units have a responsibility for this task on a rolling basis, including the 9,810 personnel based in Scotland.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2015-12-15T16:27:08.593Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436205/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436205/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436205/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-12-08","Armed Forces: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, with reference to paragraph 4.98 in the Strategic Defence and Security Review, published on 23 November 2015; how many of the 10,000 military personnel available to assist civil authorities are (a) based in Scotland and (b) available to be used to assist civil authorities in Scotland.","false","Biography information for Steven Paterson","Stirling","Steven Paterson","19186"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436206","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-12-14","<br /><p>The annual cost of Armed Forces Veterans' Badges from November 2014 to October 2015 was £44,655.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2015-12-14T16:21:51.863Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436206/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436206/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436206/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-12-08","Veterans: Military Decorations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what the annual cost is of the veterans badge.","false","Biography information for Melanie Onn","Great Grimsby","Melanie Onn","19126"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436207","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-12-14","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave on 3 December 2015 to Question number 17839 from the hon. Member for Garston and Halewood (Maria Eagle).</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2015-12-14T16:12:37.273Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436207/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436207/answer","Hansard Extract 3 December 2015 HOC 17839.docx","Military Aircraft","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436207/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-12-08","Maritime Patrol Aircraft","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what steps his Department is taking to maintain Maritime Patrol Aircraft capabilities during the period before the first Poseidon P-8 is planned to enter service in 2019-20.","false","Biography information for Douglas Chapman","Dunfermline and West Fife","Douglas Chapman","19125"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436208","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-12-14","<p>Six Tornado aircraft operating over Syria and Iraq are fitted with the Honeywell Traffic Alert and Collision Avoidance System (TCAS) II, a system designed to de-conflict aircraft operating in civil airspace. This is the first system to be deployed in a combat jet fleet globally, although TCAS is not used in operational theatres for security reasons.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2015-12-14T16:37:08.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436208/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436208/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436208/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-12-08","Military Aircraft: Safety Measures","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many Tornado and Typhoon jets operating in the Iraq and Syria region are fitted with the TCASS II Collision Warning System.","false","Biography information for Douglas Chapman","Dunfermline and West Fife","Douglas Chapman","19181"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436209","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-12-14","<p>The Committee on the Grant of Honours, Decorations and Medals (HD Committee) examined the proposals to institute a National Defence Medal (NDM) as part of the independent Military Medals Review in July 2014. The Committee was not persuaded that a strong enough case could be made at the time. Therefore the Department has no current plans to introduce a NDM for veterans.</p><br /><p>At the conclusion of Sir John Holmes review, a series of papers were placed in the Library of the House (<a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/business-papers/commons/deposited-papers/?fd=2014-07-28&amp;td=2014-07-29#toggle-1168" target="_blank">http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/business-papers/commons/deposited-papers/?fd=2014-07-28&amp;td=2014-07-29#toggle-1168</a>). One of these, ‘Revised National Defence Medal – Updated’, contains an estimate of the potential cost of awarding a NDM to all veterans who have completed four years of regular or Reserve Service or completed national service (back to 9 September 1945). Based on an approximate figure of seven million recipients the cost was estimated to be £475 million.</p><br />","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster","19128","2015-12-14T16:26:23.707Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436209/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436209/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436209/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-12-08","Veterans: Military Decorations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what plans he has to introduce a National Defence Medal for all veterans.","false","Biography information for Melanie Onn","Great Grimsby","Melanie Onn","19127"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436210","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-12-14","<p>The Committee on the Grant of Honours, Decorations and Medals (HD Committee) examined the proposals to institute a National Defence Medal (NDM) as part of the independent Military Medals Review in July 2014. The Committee was not persuaded that a strong enough case could be made at the time. Therefore the Department has no current plans to introduce a NDM for veterans.</p><br /><p>At the conclusion of Sir John Holmes review, a series of papers were placed in the Library of the House (<a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/business-papers/commons/deposited-papers/?fd=2014-07-28&amp;td=2014-07-29#toggle-1168" target="_blank">http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/business-papers/commons/deposited-papers/?fd=2014-07-28&amp;td=2014-07-29#toggle-1168</a>). One of these, ‘Revised National Defence Medal – Updated’, contains an estimate of the potential cost of awarding a NDM to all veterans who have completed four years of regular or Reserve Service or completed national service (back to 9 September 1945). Based on an approximate figure of seven million recipients the cost was estimated to be £475 million.</p><br />","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster","19127","2015-12-14T16:26:23.793Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436210/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436210/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436210/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-12-08","Veterans: Military Decorations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what assessment he has made of the potential annual cost of awarding a National Defence Medal to all veterans.","false","Biography information for Melanie Onn","Great Grimsby","Melanie Onn","19128"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436211","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-12-16","<p>The Ministry of Defence audits the integrity of the UK's nuclear deterrent regularly for all threats and hazards and acts to ensure that it maintains the highest possible standards. The Strategic Defence and Security Review acknowledges the growing cyber threat and the importance of investing in cyber security across all of our capabilities. The Government has invested £860 million in new technology and capabilities since 2011 and will invest £1.9 billion over the next five years in protecting the UK from cyber attack and developing our sovereign capabilities in cyberspace. Our approach to protecting Defence capabilities against and mitigating the impact of cyber attacks spans technical, organisational, procedural and physical measures benefiting many different systems and networks, and investment is integrated across these measures. Submarines operate in isolation by design, and this contributes to their cyber resilience. I will not discuss further details for reasons of safeguarding national security.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","19228","2015-12-16T16:17:28.323Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436211/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436211/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436211/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-12-08","Trident: Electronic Warfare","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how much his Department has spent on ensuring the Trident nuclear weapon system from cyber-attacks in each of the last three years; and how much he plans to spend in each of the next five years.","false","Biography information for Steven Paterson","Stirling","Steven Paterson","19229"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436212","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-12-16","<p>The Ministry of Defence audits the integrity of the UK's nuclear deterrent regularly for all threats and hazards and acts to ensure that it maintains the highest possible standards. The Strategic Defence and Security Review acknowledges the growing cyber threat and the importance of investing in cyber security across all of our capabilities. The Government has invested £860 million in new technology and capabilities since 2011 and will invest £1.9 billion over the next five years in protecting the UK from cyber attack and developing our sovereign capabilities in cyberspace. Our approach to protecting Defence capabilities against and mitigating the impact of cyber attacks spans technical, organisational, procedural and physical measures benefiting many different systems and networks, and investment is integrated across these measures. Submarines operate in isolation by design, and this contributes to their cyber resilience. I will not discuss further details for reasons of safeguarding national security.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","19229","2015-12-16T16:17:28.26Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436212/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436212/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436212/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-12-08","Trident: Electronic Warfare","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what assessment he has made of the threat posed to the Trident nuclear weapon system by cyber-attacks; and what steps he is taking to ensure that system is secure against such attacks.","false","Biography information for Steven Paterson","Stirling","Steven Paterson","19228"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436213","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-12-15","<p>As stated in paragraph 4.72 of the 2015 Strategic Defence and Security Review: &quot;Work continues to determine the optimum life of the UK's existing nuclear warhead stockpile and the range of replacement options. A replacement warhead is not required until at least the late 2030s, possibly later. Given lead times, however, a decision on replacing the warhead may be required in this Parliament or early in the next.&quot; The Government will inform Parliament of its intended approach in due course.</p>","Sevenoaks","Michael Fallon",,"2015-12-15T16:24:45.98Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436213/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436213/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436213/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-12-08","Nuclear Weapons","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether Parliament will be asked to vote on a decision to replace the warheads used for the successor nuclear weapon programme.","false","Biography information for Martyn Day","Linlithgow and East Falkirk","Martyn Day","19252"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436214","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-12-15","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer given by my hon. Friend the Minister for Defence Procurement (Mr Dunne) on 3 December 2015 to Question number 17976 to the hon. Member for Newport West (Paul Flynn).</p>","Sevenoaks","Michael Fallon",,"2015-12-15T16:25:27.943Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436214/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436214/answer","Hansard Extract 3 December 2015 HOC 17976.docx","Nuclear Weapons","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436214/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-12-08","Trident","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, with reference to the Strategic Defence and Security Review, if he will publish the membership of the team set up to deal with the Trident successor programme.","false","Biography information for Martyn Day","Linlithgow and East Falkirk","Martyn Day","19253"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436215","Department for Education","false","2015-12-14","<p>At present, I am unable to provide detailed information on the budget for the Regional Schools Commissioners for each of the next three years.</p><br /><p>The Department’s spending review settlement was agreed in November. The Department has now begun a business planning process to devolve this budget internally to specific activities and functions. This work is intended to finish in early 2016, when the future budgets for all the Regional School Commissioners’ offices, including the South-Central and North-West London office, will be agreed for the next financial year (2016-17) and beyond.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson","19269","2015-12-14T17:03:41.65Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436215/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436215/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436215/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-12-08","Regional Schools Commissioners","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what the budget for the Regional Schools Commissioner for South-Central England and North-West London is for each of the next three years; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Gareth Thomas","Harrow West","Gareth Thomas","19278"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436216","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-12-20","<p>We are working through the policy implications of the levy. Ministers and officials are conducting end to end meetings with a wide variety of organisations in the public and private sectors as part of the process of getting the detailed design of the levy right before its implementation in 2017.</p><br /><p>We want 16-18 year olds to play a key part in the success of apprenticeships. The lifetime benefits associated with the acquisition of apprenticeships are significant, and there is a high level of return to investment delivered by the apprenticeship programme. We will continue to encourage employers to take on 16-18 year olds as apprentices.</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2015-12-20T08:29:42.847Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436216/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436216/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436216/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-12-08","Apprentices: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, with reference to paragraph 6.14 of English Apprenticeships: Our 2020 Vision, what steps his Department will take to ensure employers are still encouraged to take on 16 to 18 apprentices following the introduction of the apprenticeship levy.","false","Biography information for Peter Kyle","Hove","Peter Kyle","19282"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436217","Department for Education","false","2015-12-14","<p>Information on the number of prospective adopters receiving approval was first collected from all adoption agencies during the year ending 2013.</p><p>In 2013 and 2014 this data was collected by Ofsted and figures are published at the following link:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/childrens-social-care-statistics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/childrens-social-care-statistics</a></p><p>Since 2014, the data has been collected as part of the Adoption Leadership Board (ALB) quarterly adoption survey and figures are published at the following link:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/adoption-system-performance" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/adoption-system-performance</a></p><p>The number of children who received an adoption decision maker (ADM) decision that the child should be placed for adoption during each of the last five years is published in table E4 of the “Children Looked After in England (including adoption and care leavers)” Statistical First Release (SFR), published at the following link:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/children-looked-after-in-england-including-adoption-2014-to-2015" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/children-looked-after-in-england-including-adoption-2014-to-2015</a></p><br /><p>Figures for the last five years are provided in table 2 below:</p><p><em></em></p><p><em>Table 2 – Number of ADM decisions during the year ending 31 March</em></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>2010</p></td><td><p>3,910</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>4,830</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>5,690</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>6,520</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>6,170</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><em>Source: SSDA903 data collection</em></p><br /><p>Ofsted publishes local authority level information on the number of children in foster placements that are subject to concurrent planning. The information is available via the following links:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/fostering-in-england-1-april-2012-to-31-march-2013" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/fostering-in-england-1-april-2012-to-31-march-2013</a></p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/fostering-in-england-1-april-2013-to-31-march-2014" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/fostering-in-england-1-april-2013-to-31-march-2014</a></p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/fostering-in-england-1-april-2014-to-31-march-2015" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/fostering-in-england-1-april-2014-to-31-march-2015</a></p><br /><p>During 2014-15, we provided a grant of £199,520 for the British Association of Adoption and Fostering in order to provide training to social workers. This grant included training for social workers on fostering for adoption.</p><br /><p>We do not collect information centrally on which local authorities have contracted out their adoption functions to a third party.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson","19261 ; 19262 ; 19263","2015-12-14T16:39:17.683Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436217/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436217/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436217/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-12-08","Adoption","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many people have been appointed as prospective adopters in each of the last six years.","true","Biography information for Tim Loughton","East Worthing and Shoreham","Tim Loughton","19260"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436218","Department for Education","false","2015-12-14","<p>Information on the number of prospective adopters receiving approval was first collected from all adoption agencies during the year ending 2013.</p><p>In 2013 and 2014 this data was collected by Ofsted and figures are published at the following link:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/childrens-social-care-statistics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/childrens-social-care-statistics</a></p><p>Since 2014, the data has been collected as part of the Adoption Leadership Board (ALB) quarterly adoption survey and figures are published at the following link:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/adoption-system-performance" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/adoption-system-performance</a></p><p>The number of children who received an adoption decision maker (ADM) decision that the child should be placed for adoption during each of the last five years is published in table E4 of the “Children Looked After in England (including adoption and care leavers)” Statistical First Release (SFR), published at the following link:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/children-looked-after-in-england-including-adoption-2014-to-2015" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/children-looked-after-in-england-including-adoption-2014-to-2015</a></p><br /><p>Figures for the last five years are provided in table 2 below:</p><p><em></em></p><p><em>Table 2 – Number of ADM decisions during the year ending 31 March</em></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>2010</p></td><td><p>3,910</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>4,830</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>5,690</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>6,520</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>6,170</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><em>Source: SSDA903 data collection</em></p><br /><p>Ofsted publishes local authority level information on the number of children in foster placements that are subject to concurrent planning. The information is available via the following links:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/fostering-in-england-1-april-2012-to-31-march-2013" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/fostering-in-england-1-april-2012-to-31-march-2013</a></p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/fostering-in-england-1-april-2013-to-31-march-2014" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/fostering-in-england-1-april-2013-to-31-march-2014</a></p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/fostering-in-england-1-april-2014-to-31-march-2015" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/fostering-in-england-1-april-2014-to-31-march-2015</a></p><br /><p>During 2014-15, we provided a grant of £199,520 for the British Association of Adoption and Fostering in order to provide training to social workers. This grant included training for social workers on fostering for adoption.</p><br /><p>We do not collect information centrally on which local authorities have contracted out their adoption functions to a third party.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson","19260 ; 19261 ; 19263","2015-12-14T16:39:17.84Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436218/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436218/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436218/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-12-08","Adoption","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many children have been subject of concurrent planning for adoption in each of the last six years in each local authority; and what funding her Department has provided to (a) carers and (b) the British Association for Adoption and Fostering in each of the last five years.","true","Biography information for Tim Loughton","East Worthing and Shoreham","Tim Loughton","19262"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436219","Department for Education","false","2015-12-14","<p>Information on the number of prospective adopters receiving approval was first collected from all adoption agencies during the year ending 2013.</p><p>In 2013 and 2014 this data was collected by Ofsted and figures are published at the following link:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/childrens-social-care-statistics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/childrens-social-care-statistics</a></p><p>Since 2014, the data has been collected as part of the Adoption Leadership Board (ALB) quarterly adoption survey and figures are published at the following link:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/adoption-system-performance" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/adoption-system-performance</a></p><p>The number of children who received an adoption decision maker (ADM) decision that the child should be placed for adoption during each of the last five years is published in table E4 of the “Children Looked After in England (including adoption and care leavers)” Statistical First Release (SFR), published at the following link:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/children-looked-after-in-england-including-adoption-2014-to-2015" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/children-looked-after-in-england-including-adoption-2014-to-2015</a></p><br /><p>Figures for the last five years are provided in table 2 below:</p><p><em></em></p><p><em>Table 2 – Number of ADM decisions during the year ending 31 March</em></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>2010</p></td><td><p>3,910</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>4,830</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>5,690</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>6,520</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>6,170</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><em>Source: SSDA903 data collection</em></p><br /><p>Ofsted publishes local authority level information on the number of children in foster placements that are subject to concurrent planning. The information is available via the following links:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/fostering-in-england-1-april-2012-to-31-march-2013" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/fostering-in-england-1-april-2012-to-31-march-2013</a></p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/fostering-in-england-1-april-2013-to-31-march-2014" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/fostering-in-england-1-april-2013-to-31-march-2014</a></p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/fostering-in-england-1-april-2014-to-31-march-2015" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/fostering-in-england-1-april-2014-to-31-march-2015</a></p><br /><p>During 2014-15, we provided a grant of £199,520 for the British Association of Adoption and Fostering in order to provide training to social workers. This grant included training for social workers on fostering for adoption.</p><br /><p>We do not collect information centrally on which local authorities have contracted out their adoption functions to a third party.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson","19260 ; 19261 ; 19262","2015-12-14T16:39:17.917Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436219/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436219/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436219/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-12-08","Adoption","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, which local authorities have contracted out their adoption functions to a third party; and what the name is of each such contractor.","true","Biography information for Tim Loughton","East Worthing and Shoreham","Tim Loughton","19263"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436220","Department for Education","false","2015-12-14","<p>At present, I am unable to provide detailed information on the budget for the Regional Schools Commissioners for each of the next three years.</p><br /><p>The Department’s spending review settlement was agreed in November. The Department has now begun a business planning process to devolve this budget internally to specific activities and functions. This work is intended to finish in early 2016, when the future budgets for all the Regional School Commissioners’ offices, including the South-Central and North-West London office, will be agreed for the next financial year (2016-17) and beyond.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson","19278","2015-12-14T17:03:41.743Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436220/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436220/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436220/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-12-08","Regional Schools Commissioners","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what estimate she has made of the cost of regional school commissioners in each of the next three years; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Gareth Thomas","Harrow West","Gareth Thomas","19269"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436221","Department for Education","false","2015-12-14","<p>Information on the number of prospective adopters receiving approval was first collected from all adoption agencies during the year ending 2013.</p><p>In 2013 and 2014 this data was collected by Ofsted and figures are published at the following link:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/childrens-social-care-statistics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/childrens-social-care-statistics</a></p><p>Since 2014, the data has been collected as part of the Adoption Leadership Board (ALB) quarterly adoption survey and figures are published at the following link:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/adoption-system-performance" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/adoption-system-performance</a></p><p>The number of children who received an adoption decision maker (ADM) decision that the child should be placed for adoption during each of the last five years is published in table E4 of the “Children Looked After in England (including adoption and care leavers)” Statistical First Release (SFR), published at the following link:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/children-looked-after-in-england-including-adoption-2014-to-2015" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/children-looked-after-in-england-including-adoption-2014-to-2015</a></p><br /><p>Figures for the last five years are provided in table 2 below:</p><p><em></em></p><p><em>Table 2 – Number of ADM decisions during the year ending 31 March</em></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>2010</p></td><td><p>3,910</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>4,830</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>5,690</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>6,520</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>6,170</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><em>Source: SSDA903 data collection</em></p><br /><p>Ofsted publishes local authority level information on the number of children in foster placements that are subject to concurrent planning. The information is available via the following links:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/fostering-in-england-1-april-2012-to-31-march-2013" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/fostering-in-england-1-april-2012-to-31-march-2013</a></p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/fostering-in-england-1-april-2013-to-31-march-2014" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/fostering-in-england-1-april-2013-to-31-march-2014</a></p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/fostering-in-england-1-april-2014-to-31-march-2015" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/fostering-in-england-1-april-2014-to-31-march-2015</a></p><br /><p>During 2014-15, we provided a grant of £199,520 for the British Association of Adoption and Fostering in order to provide training to social workers. This grant included training for social workers on fostering for adoption.</p><br /><p>We do not collect information centrally on which local authorities have contracted out their adoption functions to a third party.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson","19260 ; 19262 ; 19263","2015-12-14T16:39:17.76Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436221/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436221/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436221/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-12-08","Adoption","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many children have been approved for adoption in each of the last six years.","true","Biography information for Tim Loughton","East Worthing and Shoreham","Tim Loughton","19261"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436222","Department for Education","false","2015-12-16","<p>Play has an important role in supporting all young children to develop and prepare for later learning. The importance of play is recognised in the <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/early-years-foundation-stage-framework--2" target="_blank">Early Years Foundation Stage framework</a>, which states: “Each area of learning and development must be implemented through planned, purposeful play and through a mix of adult-led and child-initiated activity. Play is essential for children’s development, building their confidence as they learn to explore, to think about problems, and relate to others. Children learn by leading their own play, and by taking part in play which is guided by adults.”</p><p>Staff working in early years settings as early years educators and early years teachers are required to have an understanding different pedagogical approaches, including the role of play in supporting early learning and development. It is for individual schools and settings to provide opportunities for play for their children and pupils, including those with special educational needs.</p><p>Ofsted registers childcare provision on the Early Years Register and the General Childcare Register and conducts a regular cycle of inspection to ensure that provision meets the required quality and safety standards.</p><p>In judging the quality and standards of early years provision, Ofsted inspectors must assess the extent to which the learning and care provided by the setting meets the needs of the range of children who attend, including the needs of any children who have special educational needs or disabilities. At August 2015, 85 per cent of providers on the Early Years Register were rated good or outstanding for overall effectiveness.</p><br />","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2015-12-16T11:34:44.603Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436222/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436222/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436222/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-12-08","Children's Play: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what assessment she has made of the adequacy of support available to help families with disabled children find appropriate play opportunities.","false","Biography information for Andrew Stephenson","Pendle","Andrew Stephenson","19156"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436223","Department for Education","false","2015-12-16","<p>Physical education (PE) is a compulsory subject at all four key stages in the national curriculum for maintained schools in England. It sets out the expectation that pupils should be provided with opportunities to engage in a broad range of competitive sports and activities. Teachers have the flexibility to organise and deliver a range of activities; this can include rifle shooting where teachers have the specific expertise.</p><p>The government announced in the summer that it was allocating £50m from LIBOR fines to support the cadet expansion programme. This will deliver the Prime Minister's commitment to expand the number of cadet units to 500 across the UK by 2020.</p><p>The Cadet Expansion programme is a joint MOD/DfE initiative. Cadet units aim to build character, discipline and leadership skills, particularly among disadvantaged young people, through military themed activities. Cadets will have the opportunity to experience rifle shooting as part of the cadet syllabus under the supervision of fully trained Cadet Force Adult Volunteers.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2015-12-16T11:24:59.48Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436223/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436223/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436223/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-12-08","Children: Gun Sports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if she will take steps to encourage school children to participate in rifle shooting (a) sports and (b) as part of armed forces cadet activities.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","19115"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436224","Department for Education","false","2016-01-08","<p>All bullying is unacceptable and every school is required to have a behaviour policy including measures to tackle all forms of bullying. They are held to account by Ofsted and inspectors will look at records and analysis of bullying, discriminatory and prejudicial behaviour, including racist, disability, use of derogatory language and racist incidents.</p><p>The Longitudinal Study of Young People in England published in November 2015 found that 30,000 fewer young people said they had been bullied in the last twelve months - a drop from 41 per cent in 2004 to 36 per cent in 2014.</p><p>All schools are required to promote the fundamental British values of democracy, the rule of law, individual liberty and mutual respect and tolerance of those with different faith and beliefs. Our guidance published in November 2014 says that British values include accepting that others of different faiths or beliefs to oneself (or having none) should be accepted and tolerated, and should not be the cause of prejudicial or discriminatory behaviour.</p><p>All publicly funded schools are required also to promote community cohesion and teach a broad and balanced curriculum. The curriculum provides many opportunities to foster tolerance and understanding. For example, as part of the history curriculum, pupils could learn about different cultures, and about how different groups have contributed to the development of Britain. The citizenship programme of study sets out a requirement for pupils to be taught about ‘the diverse national, regional, religious, and ethnic identities in the United Kingdom and the need for mutual respect and understanding’. PSHE can teach young people about the rights and responsibilities of living in a diverse community and how to respect others.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2016-01-08T08:53:39.403Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436224/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436224/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436224/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-12-08","Schools: Bullying","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps the Government is taking to tackle bullying initiated by religious intolerance in schools.","false","Biography information for Michael Tomlinson","Mid Dorset and North Poole","Michael Tomlinson","19061"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436225","Department for Education","false","2015-12-16","<p>The pupil premium provides schools with additional funding to improve the progress and attainment of pupils from disadvantaged backgrounds, with £6.25 billion provided to date. Pupil premium allocations to schools are mainly based on the number of pupils on roll at the time of the January school census who have been registered for free school meals at any point in the preceding six years.</p><br /><p>We are working to encourage all families who meet the current criteria toregisterfor free school meals. The Department’s eligibility checking system has made it much easier and quicker to check which families are entitled to free school meals.</p><br /><p>The Department has also published a registration form to help schools to identify pupils who are entitled to free school meals and the pupil premium. This is available at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/free-school-meals-and-pupil-premium-registration-form" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/free-school-meals-and-pupil-premium-registration-form</a>.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2015-12-16T15:01:25.31Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436225/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436225/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436225/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-12-08","Pupil Premium","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps she is taking to ensure the maximum take-up of the pupil premium; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Caroline Ansell","Eastbourne","Caroline Ansell","19095"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436226","Department for Education","false","2015-12-16","<p>We are determined to deliver educational excellence everywhere so that every child, regardless of background, reaches their potential. The latest statistics show that more white boys eligible for FSM are achieving the expected standard in reading, writing and mathematics at the end of primary school, rising from 51 per cent in 2012 to 59 per cent in 2015.</p><br /><p>It is unacceptable, however, that fewer than one in four white boys eligible for free school meals (FSM) achieves the expected standard at the end of secondary school.</p><br /><p>Through the pupil premium, the government is providing additional targeted money, worth £2.5 billion in this year, to help schools support their disadvantaged pupils and improve their progress and attainment.</p><br /><p>We are raising expectations further for all pupils. We are determined to ensure that every child masters the basics of literacy and numeracy at primary school, and that those who do not will re-sit the tests at secondary school. We are also committed to introducing an expectation that every child who is able studies the EBacc combination of subjects – maths, English, history or geography, a language and the sciences - up until the age of 16.</p><br /><p>We are also introducing reforms that will further help ensure high standards throughout every child’s education and tackle entrenched underperformance, particularly amongst schools serving deprived communities.</p><br /><p>The National Teaching Service (NTS) will deploy the country’s best teachers and leaders to underperforming schools that struggle to attract and retain the professionals they need. 1,500 outstanding teachers will be part of NTS by 2020.</p><br /><p>The introduction of the national funding formula for schools will ensure that funding is transparently and fairly linked to children’s needs, ending the unfair system where children from identical disadvantaged circumstances attract significantly different levels of funding, simply because of where they live.</p><br /><p>We have also made a commitment to double the percentage of disadvantaged pupils accessing higher education by 2020, and this will include a focus on children from disadvantaged backgrounds.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2015-12-16T17:33:34.45Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436226/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436226/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436226/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-12-08","Education: Disadvantaged","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps her Department is taking to increase educational attainment among white boys from low-income socio-economic groups.","false","Biography information for Craig Whittaker","Calder Valley","Craig Whittaker","19090"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436227","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-12-15","<p>In DECC’s most recently published reference scenario, Carbon Capture and Storage would generate one per cent of electricity in 2020. The UK has a carbon budget for the period 2018-22 which requires a 37% reduction in emissions on 1990 levels, which we are on track to meet and over-perform by 51 MtCO2e.</p><br />","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2015-12-15T15:28:04.953Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436227/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436227/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436227/answer","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436227/answer/previousversion/35340","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-12-08","Carbon Capture and Storage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what assessment the Government has made of the potential contribution of carbon capture and storage to the UK meeting its 2020 carbon reduction targets.","false","Biography information for Angus Brendan MacNeil","Na h-Eileanan an Iar","Angus Brendan MacNeil","19054"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436228","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-12-15","<p>The Government’s view remains that Carbon Capture and Storage (CCS) has a potential role in the long-term decarbonisation of the UK’s power and industrial sectors. There are also potential opportunities for the oil and gas and CCS industries to work together.</p><br /><p>The Wood Review identified a range of key issues faced by the maturing UK continental shelf, which the Government and industry must jointly address to deliver maximum economic recovery (MER) of UK petroleum. In response, the Government has established the Oil and Gas Authority (OGA) as a body focused on delivering MER. This has attracted strong industry support.</p><br /><p>The OGA is considering the role of CCS in the technology and decommissioning strategies it is developing and will engage with the CCS industry to ensure that opportunities between the industries are identified and explored wherever possible.</p><br /><p>DECC will continue to engage with industry and academia, to understand the potential for any future schemes to enhance oil recovery from the North Sea.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2015-12-15T15:26:18.357Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436228/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436228/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436228/answer","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436228/answer/previousversion/35341","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-12-08","Carbon Capture and Storage: North Sea Oil","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what assessment she has made of the effect of cancelling the carbon capture and storage on oil recovery from the North Sea oil field over the next 20 years.","false","Biography information for Angus Brendan MacNeil","Na h-Eileanan an Iar","Angus Brendan MacNeil","19055"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436229","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-12-15","<p>Contracts for Difference may be awarded to generators who meet the requirements of eligibility set out in the Contracts for Difference (Definition of Eligible Generator) Regulations 2014. A generating station connected to a complete CCS system is an eligible technology under those Regulations. Contracts for Difference for CCS are awarded on direction of the Secretary of State and would be subject to the circumstances at the time, including factors such as the value for money and affordability of a project and competing demands on available budgets.</p><br /> <br />","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2015-12-15T15:24:04.213Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436229/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436229/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436229/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-12-08","Carbon Capture and Storage: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, whether carbon capture and storage plants that become operational with the assistance of support not provided by her Department will be eligible to receive contracts for difference.","false","Biography information for Dr Alan Whitehead","Southampton, Test","Dr Alan Whitehead","19132"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436230","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-12-15","<p>The Government continues to view Carbon Capture and Storage (CCS) as having a potential role in the long-term decarbonisation of the UK’s power and industrial sectors. The detailed design and implementation of CCS policy changes are currently being assessed.</p><p><br></p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2015-12-15T15:33:44.883Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436230/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436230/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436230/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-12-08","Carbon Capture and Storage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, whether she plans to produce an updated version of her Department's carbon capture and storage roadmap.","false","Biography information for Dr Alan Whitehead","Southampton, Test","Dr Alan Whitehead","19133"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436231","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-12-15","<p>The Government continues to view Carbon Capture and Storage (CCS) as having a potential role in the long-term decarbonisation of the UK’s power and industrial sectors. The detailed design and implementation of CCS policy changes are currently being assessed.</p><br />","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2015-12-15T15:32:47.59Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436231/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436231/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436231/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-12-08","Carbon Capture and Storage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, whether she plans to produce an updated version of her Department's carbon capture and storage scoping document.","false","Biography information for Dr Alan Whitehead","Southampton, Test","Dr Alan Whitehead","19134"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436232","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-12-15","<p>The Government continues to view Carbon Capture and Storage (CCS) as having a potential role in the long-term decarbonisation of the UK’s power and industrial sectors. The detailed design and implementation of CCS policy changes are currently being assessed.</p><p><br></p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2015-12-15T15:31:51.48Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436232/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436232/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436232/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-12-08","Carbon Capture and Storage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what plans she has for her Department's Office of Carbon Capture and Storage.","false","Biography information for Dr Alan Whitehead","Southampton, Test","Dr Alan Whitehead","19135"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436233","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-12-15","<p>We are engaging closely with the two bidders and wider CCS industry on the implications for them of the recent decisions.</p><br />","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2015-12-15T15:31:06.003Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436233/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436233/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436233/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-12-08","Carbon Capture and Storage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what assessment she has made of investor confidence in the carbon capture and storage industry following the CCS competition.","false","Biography information for Dr Alan Whitehead","Southampton, Test","Dr Alan Whitehead","19136"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436234","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-12-15","<p>I am attending the next meeting of the Carbon Capture and Storage Development Forum later this month.</p><br />","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2015-12-15T15:29:41.763Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436234/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436234/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436234/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-12-08","Carbon Capture and Storage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, when she expects the Carbon Capture and Storage Development Forum sponsored by her Department to meet next.","false","Biography information for Dr Alan Whitehead","Southampton, Test","Dr Alan Whitehead","19137"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436235","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-12-15","<p>Officials from the Department, as well as colleagues in the Foreign and Commonwealth Office, are in regular contact with their Canadian counterparts on this and other issues related to Carbon Capture and Storage.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2015-12-15T15:29:10.41Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436235/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436235/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436235/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-12-08","Carbon Capture and Storage: Canada","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what recent discussions her Department has had with the Canadian Department of Natural Resources on the joint Statement of Co-operation with Canada on Carbon Capture and Storage.","false","Biography information for Dr Alan Whitehead","Southampton, Test","Dr Alan Whitehead","19138"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436236","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-12-14","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave the hon. Member for Bristol West on 16 November 2015 to Question No 15971:</p><br /><p><a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2015-11-10/15971/" target="_blank">http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2015-11-10/15971/</a>.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2015-12-14T15:03:38.743Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436236/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436236/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436236/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-12-08","Fracking: Countryside","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what her policy is on the extraction of shale gas  in national parks and areas of outstanding natural beauty.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","19210"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436237","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-12-16","<p>Defra was created in 2001. It is therefore not possible to provide an answer in respect of the years prior to this. Natural England was established on 1 October 2006, so no data is available until the 2006-07 financial year.</p><br /><p>The Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew, has identified that it has spent £300 on lead ammunition in the past three years, but is unable to provide a breakdown by year. Prior to this, the shooting of pests was outsourced and Kew is unable to identify the cost of ammunition provided through this service.</p><br /><p>Financial records do not always specify the type of ammunition purchased or the material from which it was made. Our records – with the caveats above – imply that Natural England has spent an average of £253 per year on lead shot since records began.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2015-12-16T12:53:39.707Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436237/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436237/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436237/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-12-08","Lead: Ammunition","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how much was spent on lead ammunition by her Department, its agencies and non-departmental public bodies in each year since 1999.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","19242"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436238","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-12-14","<p>The Dogs Trust’s report highlights that responsibility for stopping the illegal movement of puppies begins in the country where they are born. The UK Chief Veterinary Officer has written to the authorities in the countries highlighted in the report to remind them of their duty to ensure that the requirements of the EU pet travel scheme must be fully complied with. This approach has previously resulted in investigations in EU Member States and appropriate action being taken, including the suspension of veterinarians’ licenses. We will continue to alert the authorities in any Member State where we become aware of issues in relation to the operation of the pet travel scheme.</p><p>The UK carries out more checks on pets at the border than most other EU Member States. In order to carry pets, transport companies must be approved by the Animal and Plant Health Agency to ensure that they have the necessary facilities and trained staff. It is a condition of approval that the transport company check 100% of those pets declared to them for compliance with the EU pet travel scheme. Stringent penalties are in place where people are found to be breaking the rules. Defra actively shares intelligence it gathers relating to abuse of the pet travel scheme with Local Authorities (who are enforcement bodies) and other EU countries for them to further investigate and take any necessary action.</p><p>The illegal trade is ultimately driven by demand and so we have published guidance on the steps pet owners can take to avoid buying an illegally imported pet. See: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/buying-a-cat-or-dog" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/buying-a-cat-or-dog</a>. Defra has also worked closely with the Pet Advertising Advisory Group to drive up standards for online advertisements.</p><br />","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2015-12-14T16:53:08.767Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436238/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436238/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436238/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-12-08","Dogs: Smuggling","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if she will make an assessment of the implications for her policies of the recommendations of the report by the Dogs Trust entitled Puppy Smuggling: The Scandal Continues, published in July 2015.","false","Biography information for Baroness Ritchie of Downpatrick","South Down","Ms Margaret Ritchie","19123"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436239","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-12-15","<p>In August, the Secretary of State launched the Government’s Rural Productivity Plan. This sets out a series of measures to help rural communities and businesses reach their full potential and contribute to increasing national productivity.</p><br /><p>By investing in education and skills, increasing wages, improving infrastructure and connectivity, and simplifying planning laws for rural businesses and communities, this will help create thriving rural areas where generations of families can open and expand their businesses, buy a home and educate their children at first class schools.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2015-12-15T15:50:29.6Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436239/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436239/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436239/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-12-08","Regional Planning and Development: Rural Areas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps her Department is taking to encourage economic development in rural areas within English metropolitan counties.","false","Biography information for Craig Whittaker","Calder Valley","Craig Whittaker","19089"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436240","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-12-15","<p>The vast majority of our beaches are high quality. We are determined to keep them that way and we are willing to work with all those who want to achieve this. Defra officials regularly meet Surfers Against Sewage and other environmental Non-Government Organisations to talk about the issues impacting our beaches. I would be pleased if they would contact my office to discuss a meeting.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2015-12-15T17:41:42.707Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436240/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436240/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436240/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-12-08","Beaches","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if she will meet (a) Surfers Against Sewage and (b) other charities and non-governmental organisations to discuss measures to keep the UK's beaches clean for sport and recreational activities.","false","Biography information for Mark Pritchard","The Wrekin","Mark Pritchard","19139"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436241","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-12-15","<p>Commercial cucumber growers in the UK require heated glasshouses.</p><p><strong></strong></p><p>In 2010, we introduced the National Planning Policy Framework which encourages sustainable growth in rural areas and promotes the development and diversification of agricultural and other land-based rural businesses. We aim to remove the barriers to building glasshouse nurseries.</p><p><strong></strong></p><p>There are several examples where large industrial plants have constructed substantial heated glasshouse facilities adjacent to their factory to make use of surplus heat and carbon dioxide in horticultural production. The government supports innovative initiatives of this sort.</p><br /> <br />","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2015-12-15T16:41:45.577Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436241/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436241/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436241/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-12-08","Cucumbers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps her Department is taking to (a) maintain and (b) increase the proportion of land used for growing cucumbers.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","19105"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436242","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-12-15","<p>By increasing awareness and demand for coppice products, woodland owners will be encouraged to reintroduce coppice management in their woods. For this reason, we are working with ‘Grown in Britain’, along with the Forestry Commission and the National Coppice Federation, to introduce a ‘Grown in Britain Coppice’ licence category. This will allow coppice owners and workers to benefit from the ‘Grown in Britain’ brand as it raises the profile of the home grown woodland industry.</p><br /><p>Where significant biodiversity improvement can be achieved, the practice of coppicing can also be supported through Countryside Stewardship. Under the Priority Habitat (broadleaved woodland) or Priority Species objectives of Woodland Improvement (WD2) schemes, the payment of £100 per hectare per year will be paid for activities which improve the biodiversity of woodland or make it more resilient to climate change. Where coppicing forms part of the sustainable long term management of a woodland, it can be supported though this scheme under a multi-annual agreement.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2015-12-15T16:45:56.16Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436242/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436242/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436242/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-12-08","Forests","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps her Department is taking to encourage coppicing of woodland.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","19106"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436243","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-12-15","<p>The Government does not hold information on the number of people participating in foxhunting. However, according to the Countryside Alliance around 45,000 people regularly follow hunts (<a href="http://countryside-alliance.org/support-for-boxing-day-hunts-reinforces-need-for-repeal-of-the-hunting-act/" target="_blank">http://countryside-alliance.org/support-for-boxing-day-hunts-reinforces-need-for-repeal-of-the-hunting-act/</a>).</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2015-12-15T16:52:16.96Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436243/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436243/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436243/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-12-08","Hunting","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many people participated in hunting with fox hounds in (a) 2014 and (b) 2015.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","19107"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436244","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-12-14","<p>The Government recognises the value that high-quality, locally produced food has to consumers, communities and the economy. The Great British Food Campaign was launched on 3 November to celebrate the achievements of British food and drink and to ensure that the conditions are right for its quality, creativity and reputation to flourish.</p><br /><p>2016 will be the Year of British Food. It will celebrate the quality and provenance of Britain’s producers, manufacturers, retailers and restaurateurs allowing everyone to benefit from and share the UK’s culinary heritage.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2015-12-14T17:59:56.143Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436244/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436244/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436244/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-12-08","Food","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps her Department is taking to encourage people to consume locally-sourced food produce.","false","Biography information for Craig Whittaker","Calder Valley","Craig Whittaker","19091"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436245","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-12-15","<p>This is a devolved matter, so I can only answer for England. Defra has made £900 million available for the new Countryside Stewardship scheme, launched in July 2015. For the first time ever this includes a dedicated Wild Pollinator and Farm Wildlife package. We are pleased that over half of mid–tier applications for agreements contain this package of options. The package has been developed by Natural England working in close partnership with wildlife organisations, the farming community and national pollinator scientists. This ensures it is based upon the best available evidence.</p><br /><p>Countryside Stewardship plays a key role in supporting the National Pollinator Strategy, which demonstrates the Government’s commitment to improving the status of the country’s 1,500 or so pollinating insect species. This is a programme of collaborative action and cooperation that contains a wide range of specific actions to supporthabitats for bees on farmland. In November 2015 Defra published the implementation plan for the strategy, which highlights the progress made to date, including guidance and training to farmers on supporting pollinators from the Campaign for the Farmed Environment.</p><br />","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2015-12-15T15:58:10.447Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436245/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436245/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/436245/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-12-08","Bees: Conservation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what incentives her Department provides to farmers to increase bee habitats.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","19100"
